=\n{{main|Environment of China|Water supply and sanitation in China|health in China}}\n{{more citations needed section|date=March 2016}}\n\nOver the years, large subsidies were built into the price structure of certain commodities and these subsidies grew substantially in the late 1970s and 1980s.<ref name=\"Hiroshi Sat\u014d 2006\">Hiroshi Sat\u014d. ''Unemployment, Inequality and Poverty in Urban China''. (2006) Routledge. {{ISBN|0-415-33872-7}}</ref>\n\nBy 2010, rapidly rising wages and a general increase in the standard of living had put increased energy use on a collision course with the need to reduce [[Greenhouse gas|carbon emissions]] in order to control [[global warming]]. There were diligent efforts to increase [[Efficient energy use|energy efficiency]] and increase use of [[Renewable energy|renewable sources]]; over 1,000 inefficient power plants had been closed, but projections continued to show a dramatic rise in carbon emissions from burning [[fossil fuel]]s.<ref>Keith Bradsher (5 July 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/05/business/global/05warm.html \"China Fears Consumer Class Impact on Global Warming\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723022158/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/05/business/global/05warm.html |date=23 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> Since the late 2010s, a reduction of state-backed subsidies has negatively impacted several Chinese companies, with BYD Auto being one of them.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Spotlight/Cover-Story/For-some-Chinese-companies-generous-state-subsidies-make-up-for-losses|title=For some Chinese companies, generous state subsidies make up for losses|website=Nikkei Asian Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hbr.org/2013/04/how-chinese-subsidies-changed|title=How Chinese Subsidies Changed the World|first=Usha C. V. Haley and George T.|last=Haley|date=25 April 2013|via=hbr.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1368687/the-worst-is-not-yet-over-for-byds-earnings/|title=The worst is not yet over for BYD|first=Echo|last=Huang|website=Quartz}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1683042/beijings-subsidy-cut-is-starting-to-its-largest-ev-maker-byd/|title=Beijing's subsidy cut is starting to hurt China's largest electric car company|first=Echo|last=Huang|website=Quartz}}</ref>\n\n===National debt===\n{{main|National debt of China}}\n[[File:Government debt gdp.png|thumb|250px|[[Government debt]] as a percent of GDP by IMF (2018)]]\nIn 2014, many analysts expressed concern over the overall size of China's government debt.<ref>[https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21625785-its-debt-will-not-drag-down-world-economy-it-risks-zombifying-countrys-financial \"The great hole of China\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170830143801/https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21625785-its-debt-will-not-drag-down-world-economy-it-risks-zombifying-countrys-financial |date=30 August 2017 }}, ''[[The Economist]]'', 18 October 2014</ref><ref name=\"forbes\">Kenneth Rapoza (9 May 2015), [https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2015/05/09/chinas-total-debt-load-now-over-280-of-gdp/#6830ce8367ab \"China's Total Debt Load Now Over 280% Of GDP\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923051419/https://www.forbes.com/sites/kenrapoza/2015/05/09/chinas-total-debt-load-now-over-280-of-gdp/#6830ce8367ab |date=23 September 2017 }}, ''[[Forbes]]''</ref><ref>Ye Xie (15 July 2015), [https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-15/china-s-debt-to-gdp-ratio-just-climbed-to-a-new-record-high \"China's Debt-to-GDP Ratio Just Climbed to a Record High\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170410043752/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-07-15/china-s-debt-to-gdp-ratio-just-climbed-to-a-new-record-high |date=10 April 2017 }}, ''[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]]''</ref><ref>Adair Turner (3 December 2015), [http://www.weforum.org/agenda/2015/12/how-will-china-tackle-its-debt-dilemma \"How will China tackle its debt dilemma?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312021342/http://www.weforum.org/agenda/2015/12/how-will-china-tackle-its-debt-dilemma |date=12 March 2016 }}, [[Institute for New Economic Thinking]], [[World Economic Forum]]</ref> At the end of 2014, the [[International Monetary Fund]] reported that China's general government gross debt-to-GDP ratio was 41.44 percent.<ref name=\"imfarticle\">[http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2015/cr15234.pdf \"People's Republic of China 2015 Article IV Consultation \u2013 Press Release; Staff Report; and Statement by the Executive Director for the PRC\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316161828/http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2015/cr15234.pdf |date=16 March 2016 }} IMF Country Report No. 15/234</ref><ref name=imf2015>[http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2015/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?sy=2010&ey=2017&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=924&s=NGDPD%2CNGDPDPC%2CGGXWDG_NGDP&grp=0&a=&pr.x=51&pr.y=12 World Economic Outlook Database, October 2015] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312011155/http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/weo/2015/02/weodata/weorept.aspx?sy=2010&ey=2017&scsm=1&ssd=1&sort=country&ds=.&br=1&c=924&s=NGDPD,NGDPDPC,GGXWDG_NGDP&grp=0&a=&pr.x=51&pr.y=12 |date=12 March 2016 }}, IMF</ref> In 2015, a report by the [[International Monetary Fund]] concluded that China's public debt is relatively low \"and on a stable path in all standard stress tests except for the scenario with contingent liability shocks\", such as \"a large-scale bank recapitalization or financial system bailout to deal, for example, with a potential rise in [[Non-performing loan|NPLs]] from deleveraging\".<ref name=\"IMF15234\">IMF Country Report No. 15/234, [https://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2015/cr15234.pdf People's Republic of China: Staff Report for the 2015 Article IV Consultation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160316161828/http://www.imf.org/external/pubs/ft/scr/2015/cr15234.pdf |date=16 March 2016 }} (7 July 2015).</ref>\n\nChinese authorities have dismissed analysts' worries, insisting \"the country still has room to increase government debt.\"<ref name=\"reuters\">Xiaoyi Shao and Lisa Twaronite (7 March 2016), [http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-china-economy-budget-idUKKCN0W90A2 \"China's fiscal income to slow but room for more government debt \u2013 Finance Minister\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312011820/http://uk.reuters.com/article/uk-china-economy-budget-idUKKCN0W90A2 |date=12 March 2016 }}, [[Reuters]]</ref> Former Fed Chairman [[Ben Bernanke]], earlier in 2016, commented that \"the ... debt pile facing China [is] an 'internal' problem, given the majority of the borrowings was issued in local currency.<ref>Joyce Ho (19 January 2016), [http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/Economy/Bernanke-downplays-China-impact-on-world-economy \"Bernanke downplays China impact on world economy\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312010453/http://asia.nikkei.com/Politics-Economy/Economy/Bernanke-downplays-China-impact-on-world-economy |date=12 March 2016 }} [[The Nikkei|Nikkei Asian Review]]</ref> Many economists have expressed the same views as Bernanke.<ref>[[Bill Mitchell (economist)|Bill Mitchell]] (20 January 2016), [http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=32825 \"The government really is instrumental in creating growth\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160312060436/http://bilbo.economicoutlook.net/blog/?p=32825 |date=12 March 2016 }}</ref> A 2019 survey by the [[OECD]] found that China's corporate debt is higher than other major countries.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/economics/oecd-economic-surveys-china-2019_eco_surveys-chn-2019-en|title=OECD Economic Surveys: China 2019|date=16 May 2019|website=www.oecd-ilibrary.org|page=10|doi=10.1787/eco_surveys-chn-2019-en|access-date=28 June 2019|series=OECD Economic Surveys: China|isbn=9789264312258|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191026145906/https://www.oecd-ilibrary.org/economics/oecd-economic-surveys-china-2019_eco_surveys-chn-2019-en|archive-date=26 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\"[[Shadow banking]]\" has risen in China, posing risks to the financial system.<ref>Noah Smith, [http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2016-01-07/be-scared-of-china-s-debt-not-its-crashing-stocks Be Scared of China's Debt, Not Its Stocks] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160429155129/http://www.bloombergview.com/articles/2016-01-07/be-scared-of-china-s-debt-not-its-crashing-stocks |date=29 April 2016 }}, ''[[Bloomberg View]]'' (7 January 2016).</ref><ref>[https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-banks-look-to-shadow-banking-for-growth-1446199671 Chinese Banks Look to Shadow Banking for Growth: Risks increase as third-quarter earnings show banks pushing deeper into gray markets] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170710025112/https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-banks-look-to-shadow-banking-for-growth-1446199671 |date=10 July 2017 }}, ''The Wall Street Journal'' (30 October 2015), p. 76.</ref>\n\n===Regulatory environment and government revenues===\n{{main|Tax system in China}}\nThough China's economy has expanded rapidly, its regulatory environment has not kept pace. Since Deng Xiaoping's open market reforms, the growth of new businesses has outpaced the government's ability to regulate them. This has created a situation where businesses, faced with mounting competition and poor oversight, take drastic measures to increase [[profit margin]]s, often at the expense of [[consumer safety]]. This issue became more prominent in 2007, with a number of restrictions being placed on problematic Chinese exports by the United States.<ref>An, Alex and An, David, \"Media control and the Erosion of an Accountable Party-State in China\". ''China Brief'', 7 October 2008. [http://www.jamestown.org/china_brief/article.php?articleid=2374463]{{dead link|date=April 2018|bot=InternetArchiveBot|fix-attempted=yes}}</ref>\n\nFrom the 1950s to the 1980s, the central government's revenues derived chiefly from the profits of the state enterprises, which were remitted to the state. Some government revenues also came from taxes, of which the most important was the general industrial and commercial tax.\n\nThe trend, however, has been for remitted profits of the state enterprises to be replaced with taxes on those profits. Initially, this tax system was adjusted so as to allow for differences in the [[market capitalization]] and pricing situations of various firms, but more-uniform tax schedules were introduced in the early 1990s. In addition, [[personal income]] and [[value-added tax]]es were implemented at that time.\n\n===Inflation===\n<imagemap>Image:China inflation.png|thumb|400px|Consumer price inflation in China<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20141117072912/http://www.bluenomics.com/data#!data/country_overview/key_indicators_1/consumer_price_index_cpi_hicp_inflation_/consumer_price_index_cpi_hicp_inflation_monthly_yoy_in_%7Cchart/line$countries=china&sorting=list//title \"Consumer Price Index\"].</ref></imagemap>\nDuring the winter of 2007\u20132008, inflation ran about 7% on an annual basis, rising to 8.7% in statistics for February 2008, released in March 2008.<ref name=\"CPI\">[http://www.stats.gov.cn/english/newsandcomingevents/t20071211_402451256.htm \"Consumer Price Index (CPI) Kept Growth in November\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071213174811/http://www.stats.gov.cn/english/newsandcomingevents/t20071211_402451256.htm |date=13 December 2007 }} [[National Bureau of Statistics of China]] 11 December 2007 13:14:55</ref><ref>Keith Bradsher (19 February 2008), [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/19/business/worldbusiness/19inflation.html \"China's Inflation Rose to 7.1% in January\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723022209/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/02/19/business/worldbusiness/19inflation.html |date=23 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref><ref>[http://www.stats.gov.cn/english/newsandcomingevents/t20080311_402467365.htm Consumer Price Index (CPI) Expanded in February] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080315001648/http://www.stats.gov.cn/english/newsandcomingevents/t20080311_402467365.htm |date=15 March 2008 }} [[National Bureau of Statistics of China]]\u300011 March 2008 14:53:02</ref>\n\nShortages of gasoline and diesel fuel developed in the fall of 2007 due to reluctance of refineries to produce fuel at low prices set by the state. These prices were slightly increased in November 2007 with fuel selling for $2.65 a gallon, still slightly below world prices. [[Price controls]] were in effect on numerous basic products and services, but were ineffective with food, prices of which were rising at an annual rate of 18.2% in November 2007.<ref name=\"inflation\">Keith Bradsher (14 November 2007), [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/14/business/worldbusiness/14yuan.html \"Chinese Prices Surge Again, Despite New Controls\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170916211027/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/11/14/business/worldbusiness/14yuan.html |date=16 September 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref><ref>Keith Bradsher (11 December 2007), [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/11/business/worldbusiness/11cnd-yuan.html \"Inflation Picks Up in China; Trade Gap Grows\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723022233/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/11/business/worldbusiness/11cnd-yuan.html |date=23 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]''.</ref> The problem of inflation has caused concern at the highest levels of the Chinese government. On 9 January 2008, the government of China issued the following statement on its official website: \"The Chinese government decided on Wednesday to take further measures to stabilize market prices and increase the severity of punishments for those guilty of driving up prices through hoarding or cheating.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.gov.cn/2008-01/09/content_853969.htm|title=China vows to stabilize prices, prevent price hikes|date=9 January 2008|access-date=9 January 2008|work=Chinese Government's Official Web Portal|publisher=[[Xinhua]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081201173818/http://english.gov.cn/2008-01/09/content_853969.htm|archive-date=1 December 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>Jim Yardley (9 January 2008), [https://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/09/business/worldbusiness/09cnd-yuan.html \"Fighting Inflation, China Freezes Energy Prices\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723022245/http://www.nytimes.com/2008/01/09/business/worldbusiness/09cnd-yuan.html |date=23 July 2016 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref>\n\nPork is an important part of the Chinese economy with a per capita consumption of 90 grams per day. The worldwide rise in the price of animal feed associated with increased production of ethanol from corn resulted in steep rises in pork prices in China in 2007. Increased cost of production interacted badly with increased demand resulting from rapidly rising wages. The state responded by subsidizing pork prices for students and the urban poor and called for increased production. Release of pork from the nation's strategic pork reserve was considered.<ref>{{cite news |author=Keith Bradsher |date=8 June 2007 |title=Rise in China's Pork Prices Signals End to Cheap Output |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |page=C1 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/08/business/worldbusiness/08prices.html |access-date=27 January 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190227133132/https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/08/business/worldbusiness/08prices.html |archive-date=27 February 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBy January 2008, the inflation rate rose to 7.1%, which [[BBC News]] described as the highest inflation rate since 1997, due to the [[2008 Chinese winter storms|winter storms that month]].<ref>{{cite news|title=China inflation hits 11-year high|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7252010.stm|publisher=BBC News|date=19 February 2008|accessdate=19 February 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080221015607/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7252010.stm|archive-date=21 February 2008|url-status=live}}</ref> China's inflation rate jumped to a new decade high of 8.7 percent in February 2008 after severe winter storms disrupted the economy and worsened food shortages, the government said 11 March 2008.<ref>{{cite news |title=China's inflation at decade high|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2008/BUSINESS/03/10/china.inflation/index.html|publisher=CNN|date=10 March 2008|accessdate=11 March 2008 |archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20080315002422/http://edition.cnn.com/2008/BUSINESS/03/10/china.inflation/index.html <!-- Bot retrieved archive --> |archivedate = 15 March 2008}}</ref> Throughout the summer and fall, however, inflation fell again to a low of 6.6% in October 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7719042.stm|publisher=BBC News|title=Stocks surge after China stimulus|date=10 November 2008|accessdate=1 May 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090930005120/http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7719042.stm|archive-date=30 September 2009|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nBy November 2010, the inflation rate rose up to 5.1%, driven by an 11.7% increase in food prices year on year. According to the bureau, industrial output went up 13.3 percent. As supplies have run short, prices for fuel and other commodities have risen.<ref>{{cite news|title=China inflation rate at 5.1 percent|url=http://www.timesunion.com/default/article/China-inflation-rate-at-5-1-percent-875913.php|agency=Associated Press|author=Cara Anna|date=12 December 2010|accessdate=30 December 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121211005553/http://www.timesunion.com/default/article/China-inflation-rate-at-5-1-percent-875913.php|archive-date=11 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Investment cycles===\n[[File:Beijing Financial Street (overlook).jpg|thumb|[[Beijing Financial Street]]]]\nChinese investment has always been highly cyclical.<ref>{{cite book|title=China's Economic Development: The Interplay of Scarcity and Ideology|last=Eckstein|first=Alexander|year=1976|publisher=University of Michigan Press|isbn=978-0-472-08310-7}}</ref> Ever since the 1958 Great Leap Forward, growth in fixed capital formation has typically peaked about every five years. Recent peaks occurred in 1978, 1984, 1988, 1993, 2003 and 2009. The corresponding troughs were in 1981, 1986, 1989, 1997 and 2005.\n\nIn China, the majority of investment is carried out by entities that are at least partially state-owned. Most of these are under the control of local governments. Thus booms are primarily the result of perverse incentives at the local-government level.<ref>{{cite book|title=Animal Spirits with Chinese Characteristics: Investment Booms and Busts in the World's Emerging Economic Giant|last=DeWeaver|first=Mark|year=2012|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|isbn=978-0230115699}}</ref> Unlike entrepreneurs in a free-enterprise economy, Chinese local officials are motivated primarily by political considerations. As their performance evaluations are based, to a large extent, on GDP growth within their jurisdictions, they have a strong incentive to promote large-scale investment projects.<ref>Zhou, Li'an (2004), \"Jinsheng Boyi Zhong Zhengfu Guanyuan de Jili yu Hezuo\" [Cooperation and Government Officials' Incentives in Promotion Competitions], ''Jingji Yanjiu [Economic Research]'', 6: 33\u201340.</ref><ref>Zhou, Li\u2019an (2007), \"Zhongguo Difang Guanyuan de Jinsheng Jinbiaosai Moshi Yanjiu\" [A Tournament Model of Local Government Official Promotions], ''Jingji Yanjiu [Economic Research]'', 7: 36\u201350.</ref> They also don't face any real bankruptcy risk. When localities get into trouble, they are invariably bailed out by state-owned banks. Under these circumstances, overinvestment is inevitable.\n\nA typical cycle begins with a relaxation of central government credit and industrial policy. This allows local governments to push investment aggressively, both through state-sector entities they control directly and by offering investment-promotion incentives to private investors and enterprises outside their jurisdictions.<ref>Jin, Sanlin (2004), \"Chengben Ruanyueshu Shi Touzi Guore de Zhongyau Yuanyin\" [Soft Budget Constraints Are an Important Cause of Investment Overheating], ''Zhongguo Touzi [China Investment]'', June: 37\u201339.</ref> The resulting boom puts upward pressure on prices and may also result in shortages of key inputs such as coal and electricity (as was the case in 2003).<ref>{{cite book|title=Zenme You Guo Re Le? Xin Yilun Jingji Bodong yu Hongguan Tiaokong Fenxi [Why Is There Overheating Yet Again? The New Round of Economic Fluctuation and an Analysis of Macroeconomic Adjustment]|author1=Fan Gang |author2=Zhang Xiaojing |year=2004|publisher=Jiangxi People's Publishing House|isbn=978-7-210-03077-5}}</ref> Once inflation has risen to a level at which it begins to threaten social stability, the central government will intervene by tightening enforcement of industrial and credit policy. Projects that went ahead without required approvals will be halted. Bank lending to particular types of investors will be restricted. Credit then becomes tight and investment growth begins to decline.<ref>DeWeaver, 2012</ref>\n\nEventually such centrally-imposed busts alleviate shortages and bring inflation down to acceptable levels. At that point, the central government yields to local-government demands for looser policy and the cycle begins again.\n\n==Financial and banking system==\n{{main|Chinese financial system|Banking in China|Foreign exchange reserves of the People's Republic of China|Hedge fund industry in China|China Venture Capital Association}}\nMost of China's financial institutions are state-owned and governed.<ref>p.205 Chui and Lewis Reforming China's State-Owned Enterprises and Banks 2006</ref> The chief instruments of [[finance|financial]] and [[fiscal policy|fiscal]] control are the [[People's Bank of China]] (PBC) and the [[Ministry of Finance of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Finance]], both under the authority of the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]]. The People's Bank of China replaced the [[Central Bank of China]] in 1950 and gradually took over [[private bank]]s. It fulfills many of the functions of other [[central bank|central]] and [[commercial bank]]s. It issues the currency, controls circulation, and plays an important role in disbursing budgetary expenditures. Additionally, it administers the accounts, payments, and receipts of government organizations and other bodies, which enables it to exert thorough supervision over their financial and general performances in consideration of the government's economic plans. The PBC is also responsible for [[international trade]] and other overseas [[Financial transaction|transactions]]. [[Remittance]]s by [[overseas Chinese]] are managed by the [[Bank of China]] (BOC), which has a number of branch offices in several countries.\n\nOther financial institutions that are crucial, include the [[China Development Bank]] (CDB), which funds [[economic development]] and directs [[foreign direct investment|foreign investment]]; the [[Agricultural Bank of China]] (ABC), which provides for the agricultural sector; the [[China Construction Bank]] (CCB), which is responsible for capitalizing a portion of overall investment and for providing [[capital fund]]s for certain industrial and construction enterprises; and the [[Industrial and Commercial Bank of China]] (ICBC), which conducts ordinary commercial transactions and acts as a [[savings bank]] for the public.\n\n[[File:Shanghaistockexchange.jpg|thumb|left|200px|[[Shanghai Stock Exchange]] (SSE)]]\nChina's [[Economic reform in the People's Republic of China|economic reforms]] greatly increased the economic role of the [[Banking in China|banking system]]. In theory any enterprises or individuals can go to the banks to obtain loans outside the state plan, in practice, 75% of state bank loans go to [[Government-owned corporation|State Owned Enterprises]]. (SOEs)<ref>p.11 Chui and Lewis Reforming China's State Owned Enterprises and Banks 2006</ref> Even though nearly all investment [[capital (economics)|capital]] was previously provided on a [[Grant (money)|grant]] basis according to the state plan, policy has since the start of the reform shifted to a loan basis through the various state-directed financial institutions. It is estimated that, as of 2011, 14&nbsp; trillion Yuan in loans were outstanding to local governments. Much of that total is believed by outside observers to be nonperforming.<ref name=\"Crisis\">{{cite news|last=Tatlow|first=Didi Kirsten|title=More Stimulus May Not Be an Option for China|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/22/business/global/more-stimulus-may-not-be-an-option-for-china.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=21 September 2011|accessdate=22 September 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110922160129/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/22/business/global/more-stimulus-may-not-be-an-option-for-china.html|archive-date=22 September 2011|url-status=live}}</ref> Increasing amounts of funds are made available through the banks for economic and commercial purposes. Foreign sources of capital have also increased. China has received loans from the [[World Bank]] and several [[China and the United Nations|United Nations]] programs, as well as from countries (particularly [[Sino-Japanese relations|Japan]]) and, to a lesser extent, commercial banks. [[Hong Kong]] has been a major conduit of this investment, as well as a source itself. On 23 February 2012, the PBC evinced its inclination to liberalise its capital markets when it circulated a telling ten-year timetable.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The Economist|date=3 March 2012|title=The bees get busy|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21548967|access-date=3 March 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120303141243/http://www.economist.com/node/21548967|archive-date=3 March 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> Following on the heels of this development, Shenzhen banks were able to launch cross-border yuan remittances for individuals, a significant shift in the PBC's [[capital control]] strictures since Chinese nationals had been previously barred from transferring their yuan to overseas account.<ref>{{cite news|author=Lingling Wei|newspaper=The Wall Street Journal|title=Yuan Move Chips at Capital Controls|date=29 February 2012|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2012/02/29/yuan-move-chips-at-capital-controls/|access-date=4 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923095604/https://blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2012/02/29/yuan-move-chips-at-capital-controls/|archive-date=23 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nWith two stock exchanges ([[Shanghai Stock Exchange]] and [[Shenzhen Stock Exchange]]), mainland China's stock market had a market value of $4.48 trillion as of November 2014, which makes it the second largest stock market in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-27/china-surpasses-japan-as-world-s-second-biggest-equity-market.html|title=Bloomberg - Are you a robot?|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=28 November 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141128182803/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-27/china-surpasses-japan-as-world-s-second-biggest-equity-market.html|archive-date=28 November 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2013, creation of an as yet unnamed high-level body to gather and analyze financial information and trends was announced by the central government. The central bank would participate as would people from other organizations engaged in financial matters. It would not have direct regulatory authority, but would attempt to function at the highest professional level in order to provide appropriate guidance to regulators with respect to matters such as [[shadow banking]] that are potential sources of instability.<ref name=\"NYT82013\">{{cite news |title=New Chinese Agency to Increase Financial Coordination |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/21/business/global/chinese-agency-to-increase-financial-coordination.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=20 August 2013 |author=Bettina Wassener |author2=Chis Buckley |accessdate=21 August 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130822220919/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/21/business/global/chinese-agency-to-increase-financial-coordination.html |archive-date=22 August 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> An article published in International Review of Economics & Finance in 2010 by Mete Feridun (University of Greenwich Business School) and his colleagues provide empirical evidence that financial development fosters economic growth in China.<ref name=\"Jalil, Abdul 2010 pp. 189-195\">Jalil, Abdul, Feridun, Mete and Ma, Ying (2010) Finance-growth nexus in China revisited: New evidence from principal components and ARDL bounds tests. ''International Review of Economics & Finance'', 19 (2). pp. 189\u2013195. ISSN 1059-0560 (doi:10.1016/j.iref.2009.10.005)</ref>\n\n===Stock markets===\n{{further|2015 Chinese stock market crash}}\n[[File:ChineseBullMarket.jpg|thumb|right|200 px|Cartoon that sometimes accompanied reprints of the ''People's Daily'' commentary published 21 April 2015 touting the Chinese bull market, \"What's a bubble? [[Tulip mania|Tulips]] and [[Bitcoins]] are bubbles\"<ref name=\"TNY71515\">{{cite news|author1=Evan Osnos|title=The Real Risk Behind China's Stock-Market Drama|url=https://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/the-real-risk-behind-chinas-stock-market-drama|work=The New Yorker|date=15 July 2015|accessdate=18 July 2015|quote=Wang mocked fears of a bubble\u2014\"What's a bubble? Tulips and Bitcoins are bubbles|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717234837/http://www.newyorker.com/news/daily-comment/the-real-risk-behind-chinas-stock-market-drama|archive-date=17 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>]]\nAs of 2014 and the first quarter of 2015 the financial industry had been providing about 1.5% of China's 7% annual growth rate.<ref name=\"NYT71515\">{{cite news|author1=Neil Gough|title=Cooling of China's Stock Market Dents Major Driver of Economic Growth|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/16/business/international/cooling-of-chinas-stock-market-dents-major-driver-of-economic-growth.html|work=The New York Times|date=15 July 2015|accessdate=16 July 2015|quote=In the first quarter of the year \u2013 the most recent comparison available \u2013 the output of the finance industry accounted for 1.3 percentage points of China's 7 percent growth rate.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150717133852/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/16/business/international/cooling-of-chinas-stock-market-dents-major-driver-of-economic-growth.html|archive-date=17 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nDespite slowing of the economy, as of June 2015 the Chinese stock index, the [[CSI 300 Index]], which is based on 300 stocks traded in the Shanghai and Shenzhen [[stock exchange]]s, had risen nearly 150% over the past 12 months. In an effort to forestall damage from collapse of a possible [[economic bubble]] fueled by margin trading the central government raised requirements for [[Margin (finance)|margin lending]]. Economic damage from a crash in 2007\u20132008 was limited due to margin lending being highly restricted.<ref name=\"NYT61515\">{{cite news |title=China's Unsettling Stock Market Boom |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/chinas-unsettling-stock-market-boom.html |work=The New York Times |date=15 June 2015 |author=editorial |accessdate=15 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150615160033/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/06/15/opinion/chinas-unsettling-stock-market-boom.html |archive-date=15 June 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> In early July, after a fall in the markets of nearly 30% from their 12 June highs, there were efforts by blue-chip, often state-owned, firms, the Chinese securities industry, and the central government to stabilize the market by buying back stock and increasing purchases of the stock of established firms; however, much of the volatility has been in smaller, less-established firms that had been heavily invested in by unsophisticated, often working class, investors who had purchased stock based solely on its rapid increase in valuation.<ref name=\"NYT7415\">{{cite news|author1=Keith Bradsher|author2=Chris Buckley|title=China Moves to Stabilize Stock Markets; Initial Offerings Halted|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/05/business/fund-in-china-aims-to-stabilize-stock-markets.html|date=4 July 2015|accessdate=5 July 2015|quote=the country's biggest brokerage firms unveiled a government-endorsed plan on Saturday to buy shares starting on Monday|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150705040211/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/05/business/fund-in-china-aims-to-stabilize-stock-markets.html|archive-date=5 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> 80% of Chinese stocks are owned by individual investors, many novices.<ref name=\"NYT7515\">{{cite news |author1=Keith Bradsher |author2=Chris Buckley |title=China's Market Rout Is a Double Threat |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/06/business/international/chinas-market-rout-is-a-double-threat.html |date=5 July 2015 |accessdate=5 July 2015 |quote=novices have rushed to join a national fever of speculation |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150706174001/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/06/business/international/chinas-market-rout-is-a-double-threat.html |archive-date=6 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> As of 10 July 2015 efforts by the [[China Securities Finance Corporation]], CFS, a firm created by China's commodities and stock exchanges to finance trades,<ref name=\"Caixin72815\">{{cite news |author1=Jiang Fei |author2=Zhang Yuzhe |author3=Yang Gang |author4=Yue Yue |author5=Zhang Yu |author6=Wu Hongyuran |title=Villain or Hero for Stock Market Saga? |url=http://english.caixin.com/2015-07-28/100833788.html |publisher=Caixin |date=28 July 2015 |accessdate=1 August 2015 |quote=People with knowledge of the agency's operations said it bought at least 1 trillion yuan worth of shares between 6 and 10 July. Of this amount, about 300 billion yuan was spent on 8 July. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150803050849/http://english.caixin.com/2015-07-28/100833788.html |archive-date=3 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> had apparently stabilized the market.<ref name=\"NYT8915\">{{cite news|author1=James B. Stewart|title=Why China's Stock Market Bailout Just Might Work|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/10/business/international/why-chinas-stock-market-bailout-just-might-work.html|work=The New York Times|date=9 July 2015|accessdate=11 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150713002844/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/10/business/international/why-chinas-stock-market-bailout-just-might-work.html|archive-date=13 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT71015\">{{cite news|author1=Keith Bradsher|title=Signs of a Growing Hush in China's Economy|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/11/business/international/signs-of-a-growing-hush-in-chinas-economy.html|date=10 July 2015|accessdate=11 July 2015|quote=...$3.1 trillion in market value, much of it financed with borrowed money, has been erased since mid-June.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150711152316/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/07/11/business/international/signs-of-a-growing-hush-in-chinas-economy.html|archive-date=11 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Major Chinese securities firms were required by the [[China Securities Regulatory Commission]] to buy, and hold, a substantial amount of securities affected by the downturn. Using funds supplied by the central bank and commercial banks the China Securities Finance Corporation purchased enough stocks to halt the slide acquiring as much as 5% of the stock in some firms. Lines of credit were extended by CFS to 21 securities firms, some of which also purchased up to 5% of some companies stocks. Some of the small cap stocks acquired may be overvalued.<ref name=Caixin72815 /><ref name=\"Caixin71615\">{{cite news |author1=Jiang Fei |author2=Liu Caiping |author3=Yue Yue |title=How Beijing Intervened to Save China's Stocks |url=http://english.caixin.com/2015-07-16/100829521.html |publisher=Caixin |date=16 July 2015 |accessdate=18 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150719093239/http://english.caixin.com/2015-07-16/100829521.html |archive-date=19 July 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nChinese stocks fell about 10% during the last week of July 2015 with record breaking losses on Monday.<ref name=\"NYT73115\">{{cite news|author1=David Barboza|title=Shares in Mainland China End Worst Month in 6 Years|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/01/business/international/shares-in-mainland-china-end-worst-month-in-6-years.html|work=The New York Times|date=31 July 2015|accessdate=1 August 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150731155154/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/01/business/international/shares-in-mainland-china-end-worst-month-in-6-years.html|archive-date=31 July 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Currency system===\n{{see also|Renminbi|Chinese yuan|Currency of China}}\n[[File:1 RMB to US dollar.svg|thumb|200px|1 RMB to U.S. dollar since 1981]]\nThe [[renminbi]] (\"people's currency\") is the currency of China, denominated as the [[Chinese yuan|yuan]], subdivided into 10 [[Chinese yuan|jiao]] or 100 [[Chinese yuan|fen]]. The renminbi is issued by the [[People's Bank of China]], the monetary authority of China. The [[ISO 4217]] abbreviation is CNY, although also commonly abbreviated as \"RMB\". As of 2005 the yuan was generally considered by outside observers to be undervalued by about 30\u201340%.<ref>[https://fpc.state.gov/documents/organization/57797.pdf \"China's Currency: Brief Overview of U.S. Options] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923051121/https://fpc.state.gov/documents/organization/57797.pdf |date=23 September 2017 }} CRS Report for Congress by Jonathan E. Sanford [[Congressional Research Service]] [[The Library of Congress]] Order Code RS22338 29 November 2005</ref><ref name=\"Lipman 2011\">{{cite journal|last=Lipman|first=Joshua Klein|title=Law of Yuan Price: Estimating Equilibrium of the Renminbi|journal=Michigan Journal of Business|date=April 2011|volume=4|issue=2|url=http://michiganjb.org/issues/42/text42b.pdf|accessdate=23 May 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110727082626/http://michiganjb.org/issues/42/text42b.pdf|archive-date=27 July 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> However, in 2017, the [[International Monetary Fund|IMF]] stated that the yuan was correctly valued.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/timworstall/2015/05/26/bad-news-for-allegations-of-currency-manipulation-imf-says-chinas-yuan-correctly-valued/#6d0300a77ee2|title=Bad News For Allegations of Currency Manipulation: IMF Says China's Yuan Correctly Valued|first=Tim|last=Worstall|access-date=22 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923051556/https://www.forbes.com/sites/timworstall/2015/05/26/bad-news-for-allegations-of-currency-manipulation-imf-says-chinas-yuan-correctly-valued/#6d0300a77ee2|archive-date=23 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe renminbi is held in a floating [[exchange-rate]] system managed primarily against the [[US dollar]]. On 21 July 2005, China revalued its currency by 2.1% against the US dollar and, since then has moved to an exchange rate system that references a basket of currencies and has allowed the renminbi to fluctuate at a daily rate of up to half a percent.\n\nThe [[rate of exchange]] (Chinese yuan per US$1) on 31 July 2008, was RMB 6.846, in mid-2007 was RMB 7.45, while in early 2006 was RMB 8.07:US$1=8.2793 yuan (January 2000), 8.2783 (1999), 8.2790 (1998), 8.2898 (1997), 8.3142 (1996), 8.3514 (1995).\n\nThere is a complex relationship between China's [[balance of trade]], inflation, measured by the [[consumer price index]] and the value of its currency. Despite allowing the value of the yuan to \"float\", China's [[central bank]] has decisive ability to control its value with relationship to other currencies. Inflation in 2007, reflecting sharply rising prices for meat and fuel, is probably related to the worldwide rise in commodities used as animal feed or as fuel. Thus rapid rises in the value of the yuan permitted in December 2007 are possibly related to efforts to mitigate inflation by permitting the renminbi to be worth more.<ref>Keith Bradsher )29 December 2007), [https://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/29/business/worldbusiness/29yuan.html \"China Lets Currency Appreciate a Bit Faster\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170208035615/http://www.nytimes.com/2007/12/29/business/worldbusiness/29yuan.html |date=8 February 2017 }} ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref> An article published in International Review of Economics & Finance in 2010 by Mete Feridun (University of Greenwich Business School) and his colleagues provide empirical evidence that financial development fosters economic growth in China.<ref name=\"Jalil, Abdul 2010 pp. 189-195\"/>\n\nDuring the week of 10 August 2015, against the background of a slowing Chinese economy and appreciation of the U.S. dollar, the People's Bank of China devalued the renminbi by about 5%.<ref name=\"NYT81315\">{{cite news |author1=Neil Gough |title=China Seeks to Calm Markets as It Devalues Currency for 3rd Consecutive Day |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/14/business/international/china-devalues-its-currency-renminbi-for-a-third-consecutive-day.html |work=The New York Times |date=13 August 2015 |accessdate=13 August 2015 |quote=...policy makers say they will give market forces greater sway over currency's value. The official exchange rate will be set based on the renminbi's trading performance.... |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150813105240/http://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/14/business/international/china-devalues-its-currency-renminbi-for-a-third-consecutive-day.html |archive-date=13 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> The devaluation was accomplished by pegging the official rate to closing market rates. A market-based \"representative\" exchange rate against the U.S. dollar is one of the requirements for designation of a currency as one with [[special drawing rights|Special Drawing Rights]] (SDR) by the [[International Monetary Fund]] (IMF), one of China's goals.<ref name=\"Caixin81915\">{{cite news |title=Progress for Reform as Yuan Inches toward SDR |url=http://english.caixin.com/2015-08-19/100841370.html |publisher=Caixin |date=19 August 2015 |accessdate=19 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150821024521/http://english.caixin.com/2015-08-19/100841370.html |archive-date=21 August 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref> Since the late-2000s, China has sought to [[Internationalization of the renminbi|internationalize the renminbi]]. As of 2013, the RMB is the 8th most widely traded currency in the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=RMB now 8th most widely traded currency in the world|url=http://www.swift.com/about_swift/shownews?param_dcr=news.data/en/swift_com/2013/PR_RMB_september.xml|publisher=[[Society for Worldwide Interbank Financial Telecommunication]]|accessdate=10 October 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151105223715/http://www.swift.com/about_swift/shownews?param_dcr=news.data%2Fen%2Fswift_com%2F2013%2FPR_RMB_september.xml|archive-date=5 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In November 2015 in advance of [[2015 G-20 Antalya summit|G-20]] and IMF meetings, IMF director [[Christine Lagarde]] announced her support for adding the yuan to the SDR currency basket. The announcement gave 'green-light' to official approval at 30 November IMF meeting.<ref>Talley, Ian,[https://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-yuan-should-be-an-imf-reserve-currency-christine-lagarde-says-1447459802 \"Chinese Yuan Should Be an IMF Reserve Currency, Christine Lagarde Says\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160910074450/http://www.wsj.com/articles/chinese-yuan-should-be-an-imf-reserve-currency-christine-lagarde-says-1447459802 |date=10 September 2016 }}, ''The Wall Street Journal'', 13 November 2015, retrieved 14 November 2015.</ref>\n\n==Sectors==\n\n===Agriculture===\n{{main|Agriculture in China}}\n[[File:Jiangxia-peanuts-9707.jpg|thumb|left|[[Peanut]] harvest in [[Jiangxia District]], [[Hubei]]]]\nChina is the world's largest producer and consumer of agricultural products&nbsp;\u2013 and some 300&nbsp;million Chinese [[farm]] workers are in the industry, mostly laboring on pieces of land about the size of U.S farms. Virtually all [[arable land]] is used for food [[crop]]s. China is the world's largest producer of [[rice]] and is among the principal sources of [[wheat]], corn ([[maize]]), [[tobacco]], [[soybeans]], [[potato]]es, [[sorghum]], [[peanut]]s, [[tea]], [[millet]], [[barley]], [[oilseed]], [[pork]], and [[fish]]. Major non-food crops, including cotton, other fibers, and [[oilseed]]s, furnish China with a small proportion of its foreign trade revenue. Agricultural exports, such as vegetables and fruits, fish and shellfish, grain and meat products, are exported to [[Hong Kong]]. Yields are high because of [[intensive cultivation]], for example, China's cropland area is only 75% of the U.S. total, but China still produces about 30% more crops and livestock than the United States. China hopes to further increase agricultural production through improved plant stocks, [[fertilizer]]s, and technology.\n\nAccording to the government statistics issued in 2005,<ref>{{cite web|title=Output of Farming, Animal Husbandry and Fishery|publisher=China Statistical Book|year=2005|url=http://www.allcountries.org/china_statistics/13_2_output_of_farming_animal_husbandry.html|access-date=19 November 2009|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101204081540/http://www.allcountries.org/china_statistics/13_2_output_of_farming_animal_husbandry.html|archive-date=4 December 2010|url-status=live}}</ref> after a drop in the yield of farm crops in 2000, output has been increasing annually.\n\n[[File:China-wheat-prod.png|thumb|300px|Production of [[wheat]] from 1961 to 2004 (data from [[FAO]] in 2005, y-axis: production in metric tons)]]\nAccording to the United Nations [[World Food Program]], in 2003, China fed 20 percent of the world's population with only 7 percent of the world's [[arable land]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wfp.org/country_brief/indexcountry.asp?region=5&section=9&sub_section=5&country=156|title=WFP&nbsp;\u2013 Where we work&nbsp;\u2013 China|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051025224044/http://www.wfp.org/country_brief/indexcountry.asp?region=5&section=9&sub_section=5&country=156|archivedate=25 October 2005}}</ref> China [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|ranks first]] worldwide in farm output, and, as a result of [[topography|topographic]] and [[climate|climatic]] factors, only about 10\u201315 percent of the total land area is suitable for [[Tillage|cultivation]]. Of this, slightly more than half is unirrigated, and the remainder is divided roughly equally between [[paddy field]]s and [[irrigated]] areas. Nevertheless, about 60 percent of the population lives in the rural areas, and until the 1980s a high percentage of them made their living directly from farming. Since then, many have been encouraged to leave the fields and pursue other activities, such as [[light manufacturing]], commerce, and transportation; and by the mid-1980s farming accounted for less than half of the value of rural output. Today, agriculture contributes only 13% of China's GDP.\n\n[[Animal husbandry]] constitutes the second most important component of agricultural production. China is the world's leading producer of pigs, chickens, and eggs, and it also has sizable herds of sheep and cattle. Since the mid-1970s, greater emphasis has been placed on increasing the [[livestock]] output. China has a long tradition of ocean and freshwater fishing and of [[aquaculture]]. [[Pond raising]] has always been important and has been increasingly emphasized to supplement coastal and inland [[fisheries]] threatened by [[overfishing]] and to provide such valuable export commodities as [[prawn]]s.\n\n[[File:Chiling - P1260474.JPG|thumb|Timber transported from a woodlot in the hills of [[Zhangpu County]], Fujian]]\nEnvironmental problems such as floods, drought, and erosion pose serious threats to farming in many parts of the country. The wholesale destruction of forests gave way to an energetic [[reforestation]] program that proved inadequate, and forest resources are still fairly meagre.<ref>[http://www.iges.or.jp/en/fc/pdf/activity/plantation_china.pdf Plantation Study in China: Research Outline] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216014926/http://www.iges.or.jp/en/fc/pdf/activity/plantation_china.pdf |date=16 February 2008 }} Forest Conservation Project, Institute for Global Environmental Strategies, Japan; February 2006.</ref> The principal forests are found in the [[Qinling|Qin Mountains]] and the central mountains and on the [[Yunnan\u2013Guizhou Plateau]]. Because they are inaccessible, the Qinling forests are not worked extensively, and much of the country's [[timber]] comes from [[Heilongjiang]], [[Jilin]], [[Sichuan]], and [[Yunnan]].\n\n[[Western China]], comprising [[Tibet Autonomous Region|Tibet]], [[Xinjiang]], and [[Qinghai]], has little agricultural significance except for areas of [[floriculture]] and [[cattle raising]]. Rice, China's most important crop, is dominant in the southern provinces and many of the farms here yield two [[harvests]] a year. In the north, wheat is of the greatest importance, while in [[central China]] wheat and rice vie with each other for the top place. [[Millet]] and [[kaoliang]] (a variety of grain sorghum) are grown mainly in the northeast and some central provinces, which, together with some northern areas, also provide considerable quantities of [[barley]]. Most of the [[soybean]] crop is derived from the north and the northeast; corn (maize) is grown in the center and the north, while [[tea]] comes mainly from the warm and humid hilly areas of the south. Cotton is grown extensively in the central provinces, but it is also found to a lesser extent in the southeast and in the north. [[Tobacco]] comes from the center and parts of the south. Other important crops are potatoes, [[sugar beet]]s, and oilseeds.\n\n[[File:Daye-pond-system-fishermen-0078-rotated.jpg|thumb|Fish ponds near [[Daye, Hubei]]]]\nIn the past decade, the government has been encouraging agricultural mechanization and land consolidation to raise yields and compensate for the loss of rural workers who have migrated to the cities.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Stanway|first1=David|title=Analysis: China turns to machines as farmers seek fresh fields|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-agriculture-mechanisation/analysis-china-turns-to-machines-as-farmers-seek-fresh-fields-idUSBRE8AC15P20121114|accessdate=26 November 2017|agency=Reuters|date=14 November 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201032547/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-agriculture-mechanisation/analysis-china-turns-to-machines-as-farmers-seek-fresh-fields-idUSBRE8AC15P20121114|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> According to the most recent statistics by the UN Food and Agriculture Organization, the annual growth rate of agricultural mechanization in China is 6.38 percent. By 2014, the integrated mechanization rate had risen to nearly 60 percent, with the rate for wheat surpassing 90 percent and that for maize approaching 80 percent.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Cheng|first1=Fang|title=Development of Agricultural Mechanization in China|url=https://forum2017.iamo.de/microsites/forum2017.iamo.de/fileadmin/presentations/B5_Fang.pdf|website=Eurasian Food Economy Forum 2017|publisher=UN Food and Agriculture Organization|accessdate=26 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201034946/https://forum2017.iamo.de/microsites/forum2017.iamo.de/fileadmin/presentations/B5_Fang.pdf|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition to standard agricultural equipment like tractors, China's agriculture cooperatives have begun using high-tech equipment, including unmanned aerial vehicles, which are used to spay crops with pesticides.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Schaer|first1=Lilian|title=China powers up: The world's most populous country gets serious about farming machinery|url=https://www.country-guide.ca/2017/03/24/china-gets-serious-about-farm-machinery/50781/|website=Country Guide|accessdate=26 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043537/https://www.country-guide.ca/2017/03/24/china-gets-serious-about-farm-machinery/50781/|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> Good progress has been made in increasing [[water conservancy]], and about half the cultivated land is under irrigation.\n\nIn the late 1970s and early 1980s, economic reforms were introduced. First of all this began with the shift of farming work to a [[responsibility system|system of household responsibility]] and a phasing out of [[collective farming|collectivized agriculture]]. Later this expanded to include a gradual liberalization of price controls; [[fiscal policy|fiscal]] [[decentralization]]; massive privatization of state enterprises, thereby allowing a wide variety of [[private enterprise]]s in the [[service sector|services]] and [[light manufacturing]]; the foundation of a diversified [[banking system]] (but with large amounts of state control); the development of a [[stock market]]; and the opening of the economy to increased [[foreign trade]] and [[foreign direct investment|foreign investment]].\n\n===Housing and construction===\n{{main|Real estate in China}}\nThe real estate industry is about 20% of the Chinese economy.<ref name=\"NYT61115\">{{cite news |author1=Neil Gough|title=Idle Home Builders Hold China's Economy Back |work=The New York Times |date=11 June 2015 |quote=By some economists' estimates, real estate and related industries account for more than 20 percent of China's gross domestic product}}</ref>\n\n===Energy and mineral resources===\n{{see also|Energy policy of China}}\n<div class=\"infobox\" style=\"width:20em;\">'''Electricity:'''\n* Production: 6.5 trillion kWh (2017)<ref name=\"bp.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bp.com/en/global/corporate/energy-economics/statistical-review-of-world-energy/downloads.html|title=Downloads &#124; Energy economics &#124; Home|website=BP global|access-date=15 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180615135258/https://www.bp.com/en/global/corporate/energy-economics/statistical-review-of-world-energy/downloads.html|archive-date=15 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* Consumption: 2.8248 trillion kWh (2006)\n* Exports: 18.7 billion kwh (2015)<ref name=\"data.stats.gov.cn\">data.stats.gov.cn</ref>\n* Imports: 6.2 billion kwh (2015)<ref name=\"data.stats.gov.cn\"/>\n\n'''Electricity \u2013 production by source:'''\n<imagemap>Image: Electricity Production in China.png|thumb|This chart shows the Chinese electricity production by source in time</imagemap>\n\n* Thermal: 70.4 (67.1% from coal) (2017)<ref name=\"bp.com\"/>\n* Hydro: 17.8% (2017)\n* Renewables: 7.3% (2017)\n* Nuclear: 3.8% (2017)\n* Other: 0.7% (2017)\n\n'''Oil:'''\n* Production: {{convert|3631000|oilbbl/d|abbr=on}} (2005)\n* Consumption: {{convert|6534000|oilbbl/d|abbr=on}} (2005) and expected {{convert|9300000|oilbbl/d|abbr=on}} in 2030\n* Exports: {{convert|443300|oilbbl/d|abbr=on}} (2005)\n* Imports: {{convert|3181000|oilbbl/d|abbr=on}} (2005)\n* Net imports: {{convert|2740000|oilbbl/d}} (2005)\n* Proved reserves: {{convert|16.3|Goilbbl|abbr=on}} (1 January 2006)\n\n'''Natural gas:'''\n* Production: 47.88&nbsp;km<sup>3</sup> (2005 est.)\n* Consumption: 44.93&nbsp;km<sup>3</sup> (2005 est.)\n* Exports: 2.944&nbsp;km<sup>3</sup> (2005)\n* Imports: 0 m<sup>3</sup> (2005)\n* Proved reserves: 1,448&nbsp;km<sup>3</sup> (1 January 2006 est.)\n</div>\nSince 1980, China's energy production has grown dramatically, as has the proportion allocated to domestic consumption. Some 80 percent of all power is generated from fossil fuel at [[thermal plant]]s, with about 17 percent at [[hydroelectric]] installations; only about two percent is from [[Nuclear power|nuclear energy]], mainly from plants located in [[Guangdong]] and [[Zhejiang]].<ref>[[World Nuclear Association]]. [http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/inf63.html Nuclear Power in China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130212223045/http://www.world-nuclear.org/info/inf63.html |date=12 February 2013 }} (November 2007)</ref> Though China has rich overall energy potential, most have yet to be developed. In addition, the geographical distribution of energy puts most of these resources relatively far from their major industrial users. Basically the northeast is rich in [[coal]] and [[oil]], the central part of north China has abundant coal, and the southwest has immense [[hydroelectric potential]]. But the industrialized regions around [[Guangzhou]] and the [[Yangtze River|Lower Yangtze]] region around Shanghai have too little energy, while there is relatively little [[heavy industry]] located near major energy resource areas other than in the southern part of the northeast.\n\nDue in large part to environmental concerns, China has wanted to shift China's current [[energy mix]] from a heavy reliance on coal, which accounts for 70\u201375% of China's energy, toward greater reliance on oil, [[natural gas]], [[Renewable energy in China|renewable energy]], and [[Nuclear power in China|nuclear power]]. China has closed thousands of [[coal mines]] over the past five to ten years to cut [[overproduction]]. According to Chinese statistics, this has reduced coal production by over 25%.\n\nSince 1993, China has been a net importer of oil, a large portion of which comes from the Middle East. Imported oil accounts for 20% of the processed [[Crude oil|crude]] in China. Net imports are expected to rise to 3.5&nbsp;million&nbsp;[[barrel (unit)|barrels]] (560,000&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>) per day by 2010. China is interested in diversifying the sources of its oil imports and has invested in oil fields around the world. China is developing oil imports from [[Central Asia]] and has invested in [[Kazakhstan]]i [[oil field]]s.<ref>Vakulchuk, Roman and Indra Overland (2019) \u201c[https://www.researchgate.net/publication/329310641 China\u2019s Belt and Road Initiative through the Lens of Central Asia]\u201d, in Fanny M. Cheung and Ying-yi Hong (eds) ''Regional Connection under the Belt and Road Initiative. The Prospects for Economic and Financial Cooperation''. London: Routledge, pp. 115\u2013133.</ref> Beijing also plans to increase China's natural gas production, which currently accounts for only 3% of China's total energy consumption and incorporated a natural gas strategy in its [[Tenth Five-Year Plan (People's Republic of China)|10th Five-Year Plan]] (2001\u20132005), with the goal of expanding gas use from a 2% share of total energy production to 4% by 2005 (gas accounts for 25% of U.S. energy production). Analysts expect China's consumption of natural gas to more than double by 2010.\n\nThe [[Eleventh Five-Year Plan (People's Republic of China)|11th Five-Year Program]] (2006\u201310), announced in 2005 and approved by the National People's Congress in March 2006, called for greater energy conservation measures, including development of renewable energy sources and increased attention to environmental protection. Guidelines called for a 20% reduction in energy consumption per unit of GDP by 2010. Moving away from coal towards cleaner energy sources including oil, natural gas, renewable energy, and nuclear power is an important component of China's development program. Beijing also intends to continue to improve energy efficiency and promote the use of [[clean coal technology]]. China has abundant hydroelectric resources; the Three Gorges Dam, for example, will have a total capacity of 18 gigawatts when fully on-line (projected for 2009). In addition, the share of electricity generated by nuclear power is projected to grow from 1% in 2000 to 5% in 2030. China's renewable energy law, which went into effect in 2006, calls for 10% of its energy to come from renewable energy sources by 2020.\n\n====Mining====\n{{see also|Gold mining in China}}\nOutdated [[mining]] and ore-processing technologies are being replaced with modern techniques, but China's [[industrialization of China|rapid industrialization]] requires imports of minerals from abroad. In particular, iron ore imports from [[mining in Australia|Australia]] and the United States have soared in the early 2000s as [[steel production in China|steel production]] rapidly outstripped domestic iron ore production. Also China has become increasingly active in several African countries to mine the reserves it requires for economic growth, particularly in countries such as the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] and [[Gabon]].\n\nThe major areas of production in 2004 were [[coal mining in China|coal]] (nearly 2&nbsp;billion&nbsp;tons), [[iron ore]] (310&nbsp;million&nbsp;tons), [[petroleum industry in China|crude petroleum]] (175&nbsp;million&nbsp;tons), [[natural gas]] (41&nbsp;million cubic meters), [[antimony]] ore (110,000&nbsp;tons), [[tin]] concentrates (110,000 tons), [[nickel]] ore (64,000&nbsp;tons), [[tungsten]] concentrates (67,000&nbsp;tons), unrefined [[salt]] (37&nbsp;million&nbsp;tons), [[vanadium]] (40,000&nbsp;tons), and [[molybdenum]] ore (29,000&nbsp;tons). In order of magnitude, produced minerals were [[bauxite]], [[gypsum]], [[barite]], [[magnesite]], [[talc]] and related minerals, [[manganese]] ore, [[fluorspar]], and [[zinc]]. In addition, China produced 2,450&nbsp;tons of [[silver]] and 215&nbsp;tons of [[gold]] in 2004. The mining sector accounted for less than 0.9% of total employment in 2002 but produced about 5.3% of total industrial production.\n\n====Hydroelectric resources====\n[[File:Dreischluchtendamm hauptwall 2006.jpg|thumb|Three Gorges Dam]]\nChina has an abundant potential for [[hydroelectric power]] production due to its considerable river network and mountainous terrain. Most of the total hydroelectric capacity is situated in the [[Southwest China|southwest of the country]], where coal supplies are poor but [[energy demand|demand for energy]] is rising swiftly. The potential in the northeast is fairly small, but it was there that the first hydroelectric stations were built\u2014by the Japanese during its occupation of [[Manchuria]].<ref>[http://www.ieee.org/portal/cms_docs_iportals/iportals/aboutus/history_center/publications/power/Chapter2.pdf Case Study of Electrification: China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080216014910/http://www.ieee.org/portal/cms_docs_iportals/iportals/aboutus/history_center/publications/power/Chapter2.pdf |date=16 February 2008 }}&nbsp;\u2013 Worldwide Electrification from the 1950s to the 1970s. (Chapter 2; page 33).</ref>\n\nThirteen years in construction at a cost of $24&nbsp;billion, the immense [[Three Gorges Dam]] across the [[Yangtze|Yangtze River]] was essentially completed in 2006 and produced more than 100TWh of energy in 2018.\n\n====Coal====\n{{main|Coal power in the People's Republic of China}}\n[[File:Coal mine in Inner Mongolia 002.jpg|thumb|Coal mining in Inner Mongolia]]\nChina is well endowed with mineral resources,<ref>[[MSN Encarta]]. [http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761574726_3/Asia.html Asia: Mineral Resources]. [https://web.archive.org/web/20040104083400/http://encarta.msn.com/encyclopedia_761574726_3/Asia.html Archived] 31 October 2009.</ref> the most important of which is [[coal]]. China's mineral resources include large reserves of [[coal]] and [[iron ore]], plus adequate to abundant supplies of nearly all other industrial [[minerals]]. Although coal deposits are widely scattered (some coal is found in every province), most of the total is located in the northern part of the country. The province of [[Shanxi]], in fact, is thought to contain about half of the total; other important coal-bearing provinces include [[Heilongjiang]], [[Liaoning]], [[Jilin]], [[Hebei]], and [[Shandong]].<ref name=\"TED China and Coal\">TED Case Studies. [http://www.american.edu/TED/chincoal.htm China and Coal] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170212013651/http://www1.american.edu/TED/CHINCOAL.HTM |date=12 February 2017 }}</ref> Apart from these northern provinces, significant quantities of coal are present in [[Sichuan]], and there are some deposits of importance in [[Guangdong]], [[Guangxi]], [[Yunnan]], and [[Guizhou]].<ref name=\"TED China and Coal\"/> A large part of the country's reserves consists of good [[bituminous coal]], but there are also large deposits of [[lignite]]. [[Anthracite]] is present in several places (especially [[Liaoning]], [[Guizhou]], and [[Henan]]), but overall it is not very significant.<ref>{{cite book|last=Heping|first=Xie|author2=Tad S. Golosinski|title=Mining Science and Technology '99|publisher=Taylor & Francis|year=1999|pages=252\u2013256|isbn=978-90-5809-067-6}}</ref>\n\nTo ensure a more even distribution of coal supplies and to reduce the strain on the less than adequate [[transportation]] network, the authorities pressed for the development of a large number of small, locally run [[coal mining|mines]] throughout the country. This campaign was energetically pursued after the 1960s, with the result that thousands of small pits have been established, and they produce more than half the country's coal. This output, however, is typically expensive and is used for local consumption. It has also led to a less than stringent implementation of safety measures in these unregulated mines, which cause several thousands of deaths each year.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Creedy|first=David|author2=Lijie, Wang |author3=Xinquan, Zhou |author4=Haibin, Liu |author5= Campbell, Gary |title=Transforming China's coal mines: A case history of the Shuangliu Mine|journal=Natural Resources Forum|volume=30|issue=1|pages=15\u201326|publisher=Blackwell Publishing|date=February 2006|doi=10.1111/j.1477-8947.2006.00154.x}}</ref>\n\n[[Coal]] makes up the bulk of China's energy consumption (70% in 2005), and China is the largest producer and consumer of coal in the world. As China's economy continues to grow, China's coal demand is projected to rise significantly. Although coal's share of China's overall energy consumption will decrease, coal consumption will continue to rise in absolute terms. China's continued and increasing reliance on coal as a power source has contributed significantly to putting China on the path to becoming the world's largest emitter of [[acid rain]]-causing [[sulfur dioxide]] and [[greenhouse gas]]es, including [[carbon dioxide]].\n\nAs of 2015, falling coal prices resulted in layoffs at coal mines in the northeast.<ref name=\"NYT121615\">{{cite news |author1=Jane Perlez |author2=Yufan Huang |title=Mass Layoffs in China's Coal Country Threaten Unrest |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/17/world/asia/china-coal-mining-economy.html |work=The New York Times |date=16 December 2015 |accessdate=17 December 2015 |quote=The coal industry is hurting nationwide, as coal prices have fallen nearly 60 percent since 2011, said Deng Shun, an analyst at ICIS C1 Energy, a consultancy based in Shanghai. |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170525020144/https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/17/world/asia/china-coal-mining-economy.html |archive-date=25 May 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n====Oil and natural gas====\n{{main|Petroleum industry in the People's Republic of China}}\n[[File:China-Today oil reserves and demand-en.svg|thumb|300px|Chinese oil reserves]]\nChina's onshore [[oil]] resources are mostly located in the [[Northeast China|Northeast]] and in [[Xinjiang]], [[Gansu]], [[Qinghai]], [[Sichuan]], [[Shandong]], and [[Henan]] provinces. [[Oil shale]] is found in a number of places, especially at [[Fushun]] in Liaoning, where the deposits overlie the coal reserves, as well as in Guangdong. High quality [[Light crude oil|light oil]] has been found in the [[Pearl River (China)|Pearl River]] estuary of the [[South China Sea]], the [[Qaidam]] Basin in Qinghai, and the [[Tarim Basin]] in Xinjiang. The country consumes most of its oil output but does export some crude oil and oil products. China has explored and developed oil deposits in the [[South China Sea]] and [[East China Sea]], the [[Yellow Sea]], the [[Gulf of Tonkin]], and the [[Bohai Sea]].\n\nIn 2013, the pace of China's economic growth exceeded the domestic oil capacity and floods damaged the nation's oil fields in the middle of the year. Consequently, China imported oil to compensate for the supply reduction and surpassed the US in September 2013 to become the world's largest importer of oil.<ref>{{cite news |title=China overtakes US as the biggest importer of oil |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24475934 |publisher=BBC News |date=10 October 2013 |accessdate=11 October 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131010171123/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-24475934 |archive-date=10 October 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe total extent of China's [[natural gas reserves]] is unknown, as relatively little exploration for natural gas has been done.<ref>[[Xinhua]]. [http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-11/25/content_394888.htm China to calculate oil and gas reserves] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080120061634/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/english/doc/2004-11/25/content_394888.htm |date=20 January 2008 }} 25 November 2004.</ref> Sichuan accounts for almost half of the known natural gas reserves and production.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chinapage.com/power/oil-gas/puguang-gasfield.html |title=Puguang Named 2nd Largest Gas Field |publisher=Chinapage.com |accessdate=28 February 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508002954/http://www.chinapage.com/power/oil-gas/puguang-gasfield.html |archivedate=8 May 2013 }}</ref> Most of the rest of China's natural gas is associated gas produced in the Northeast's major oil fields, especially [[Daqing oilfield]]. Other gas deposits have been found in the [[Qaidam]] Basin, [[Hebei]], [[Jiangsu]], [[Shanghai]], and [[Zhejiang]], and offshore to the southwest of [[Hainan Island]].<ref>Kaoru YAMAGUCHI, Keii CHO. [http://eneken.ieej.or.jp/en/data/pdf/221.pdf Natural Gas in China] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071031083248/http://eneken.ieej.or.jp/en/data/pdf/221.pdf |date=31 October 2007 }} IEEJ: August 2003.</ref> According to an article published in Energy Economics in 2011 by economists Mete Feridun (University of Greenwich) and Abdul Jalil (Wuhan University in China), financial development in China has not taken place at the expense of environmental pollution and financial development has led to a decrease in environmental pollution. Authors conclude that carbon emissions are mainly determined by income, energy consumption and trade openness and their findings confirm the existence of an Environmental Kuznets Curve in the case of China.<ref>Jalil, Abdul and Feridun, Mete (2011) \"The impact of growth, energy and financial development on the environment in China: a cointegration analysis\". ''Energy Economics'', 33 (2). pp. 284\u2013291. ISSN 0140-9883 (doi:10.1016/j.eneco.2010.10.003)</ref>\n\n====Metals and nonmetals====\n[[Iron ore]] reserves are found in most provinces, including [[Hainan]]. Gansu, Guizhou, southern Sichuan, and Guangdong provinces have rich deposits. The largest mined reserves are located north of the [[Yangtze|Yangtze River]] and supply neighboring iron and steel enterprises. With the exception of [[nickel]], [[chromium]], and [[cobalt]], China is well supplied with [[ferroalloy]]s and [[manganese]]. Reserves of [[tungsten]] are also known to be fairly large. [[Copper]] resources are moderate, and high-quality ore is present only in a few deposits. Discoveries have been reported from [[Ningxia]]. [[Lead]] and [[zinc]] are available, and [[bauxite]] resources are thought to be plentiful. China's [[antimony]] reserves are the largest in the world. [[Tin]] resources are plentiful, and there are fairly rich deposits of gold. China is the world's fifth largest producer of [[gold]] and in the early 21st century became an important producer and exporter of rare metals needed in high-technology industries.\n\nChina also produces a fairly wide range of [[nonmetal]]lic minerals. One of the most important of these is [[salt]], which is derived from coastal [[evaporation]] sites in Jiangsu, Hebei, Shandong, and Liaoning, as well as from extensive salt fields in Sichuan, Ningxia, and the Qaidam Basin. There are important deposits of [[phosphate]] rock in a number of areas; Jiangxi, Guangxi, Yunnan and Hubei. Production has been accelerating every year. As of 2013 China is producing 97,000,000 metric tons of phosphate rock a year.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://minerals.usgs.gov/minerals/pubs/commodity/phosphate_rock/mcs-2014-phosp.pdf|title=Phosphate Rock Statistics and Information|access-date=15 June 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170513090847/https://minerals.usgs.gov/minerals/pubs/commodity/phosphate_rock/mcs-2014-phosp.pdf|archive-date=13 May 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Pyrite]]s occur in several places; Liaoning, Hebei, Shandong, and Shanxi have the most important deposits. China also has large resources of [[fluorite]] ([[fluorspar]]), [[gypsum]], [[asbestos]], and has the world's largest reserves and production of [[cement]], clinker and limestone.\n\n===Industry and manufacturing===\n{{further|Industry of China|Made in China|Technological and industrial history of China}}\n[[File:China Railways HXD1B Manufacture Factory.jpg|thumb|China Railway HXD1B Manufacturing Company]]\n[[File:0B6X8331 (8272948482).jpg|thumb|[[List of high-speed railway lines in China|High-speed railway lines in China]]]]\nIndustry and construction account for 46.8% of China's GDP.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2012.html?countryName=China&countryCode=CH&regionCode=eas&#CH |title=CIA.gov |publisher=CIA |accessdate=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120224190802/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/fields/2012.html?countryName=China&countryCode=CH&regionCode=eas&#CH |archive-date=24 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Between the years 2011 and 2013, China used more cement than the United States consumed during the entire 20th century.<ref>Bill Gates (12 June 2014), [http://www.gatesnotes.com/Books/Making-the-Modern-World?WT.mc_id=06_13_2014_smilc_tw Have You Hugged a Concrete Pillar Today?] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923101356/https://www.gatesnotes.com/Books/Making-the-Modern-World?WT.mc_id=06_13_2014_smilc_tw |date=23 September 2017 }}</ref> In 2009 around 8% of the total manufacturing output in the world came from China itself and China [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|ranked third]] worldwide in industrial output that year (first was [[European Union|EU]] and second United States). Research by IHS Global Insight states that in 2010 China contributed to 19.8% of world's manufacturing output and became the largest manufacturer in the world that year, after the US had held that position for about 110 years.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hs6lMonB70QER8hngleFPHLXwnyA?docId=CNG.9cac656ee218c88029a4490458898142.391 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110320222440/http://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5hs6lMonB70QER8hngleFPHLXwnyA?docId=CNG.9cac656ee218c88029a4490458898142.391 |url-status=dead |archive-date=20 March 2011 |title=China tops US in manufacturing: study |date=14 March 2011 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Marsh |first=Peter |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/002fd8f0-4d96-11e0-85e4-00144feab49a.html?ftcamp=rss |title=China noses ahead as top goods producer |newspaper=Financial Times |date=13 March 2011 |accessdate=27 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120111105652/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/002fd8f0-4d96-11e0-85e4-00144feab49a.html?ftcamp=rss |archive-date=11 January 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n[[File:COMAC B-001A May 2017.jpg|thumb|left|[[C919]] developed by Chinese aerospace manufacturer Comac]]\n\nIn November 2012, the [[State Council of the People's Republic of China]] mandated a \"social risk assessment\" for all major industrial projects. This requirement followed mass public protests in some locations for planned projects or expansions.<ref name=\"NYT111212\">{{cite news|title='Social Risk' Test Ordered by China for Big Projects|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/13/world/asia/china-mandates-social-risk-reviews-for-big-projects.html|accessdate=13 November 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=12 November 2012|author=Keith Bradsher|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121113032446/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/13/world/asia/china-mandates-social-risk-reviews-for-big-projects.html|archive-date=13 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMajor industries include mining and ore processing; [[iron]] and [[steel]]; [[aluminium]]; [[coal]]; [[machinery]]; [[armaments]]; [[textiles]] and [[apparel]]; [[petroleum]]; [[cement]]; [[chemical]]; [[fertilizers]]; [[food processing]]; [[automobile]]s and other transportation equipment including rail cars and locomotives, ships, and aircraft; [[consumer products]] including [[footwear]], [[toy]]s, and [[electronics]]; [[telecommunications]] and [[information technology]]. China has become a preferred destination for the relocation of global manufacturing facilities. Its strength as an export platform has contributed to incomes and employment in China.\n\nSince the founding of the People's Republic, industrial development has been given considerable attention; as of 2011 46% of China's national output continued to be devoted to investment; a percentage far higher than any other nation.<ref name=\"NYT11612\">{{cite news |title=Facing Protests, China's Business Investment Slows |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/07/business/global/facing-protests-chinas-business-investment-may-be-cooling.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=6 November 2012 |author=Keith Bradsher |accessdate=7 November 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121107090110/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/07/business/global/facing-protests-chinas-business-investment-may-be-cooling.html |archive-date=7 November 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> Among the various industrial branches the [[machine]]-building and [[metallurgy|metallurgical]] industries have received the highest priority. These two areas alone now account for about 20\u201330 percent of the total gross value of industrial output.<ref name=\"FFCTMR\">{{cite web |url=http://www.florida-agriculture.com/pubs/pubform/pdf/Florida_Forestry_China_Trade_Mission_Report.pdf |title=Florida Forestry China Trade Mission Report |accessdate=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306203818/http://www.florida-agriculture.com/pubs/pubform/pdf/Florida_Forestry_China_Trade_Mission_Report.pdf |archive-date=6 March 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> In these, as in most other areas of industry, however, [[innovation]] has generally suffered at the hands of a system that has rewarded increases in gross output rather than improvements in variety, sophistication and quality. China, therefore, still imports significant quantities of specialized steels. Overall industrial output has grown at an average rate of more than 10 percent per year, having surpassed all other sectors in [[economic growth]] and degree of [[modernization]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chinability.com/Industrial%20output.htm |title=Industrial output growth 1978\u20132006 |publisher=Chinability.com |accessdate=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120228235331/http://www.chinability.com/Industrial%20output.htm |archive-date=28 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Some heavy industries and products deemed to be of national strategic importance remain state-owned, but an increasing proportion of lighter and [[consumer]]-oriented manufacturing firms are privately held or are private-state [[joint venture]]s.\n\nThe predominant focus of development in the [[chemical industry]] is to expand the output of chemical [[fertilizer]]s, [[plastics]], and [[synthetic fiber]]s. The growth of this industry has placed China among the world's leading producers of [[nitrogenous]] fertilizers. In the [[consumer goods]] sector the main emphasis is on textiles and [[clothing]], which also form an important part of China's exports. Textile manufacturing, a rapidly growing proportion of which consists of synthetics, account for about 10 percent of the gross industrial output and continues to be important, but less so than before. The industry tends to be scattered throughout the country, but there are a number of important [[textile industry in China|textile centers]], including [[Shanghai]], [[Guangzhou]], and [[Harbin]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.allcountries.org/china_statistics/14_19_output_of_major_industrial_products.html |title=14\u201319: Output of Major Industrial Products |publisher=Allcountries.org |date=26 April 2006 |accessdate=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120211212156/http://www.allcountries.org/china_statistics/14_19_output_of_major_industrial_products.html |archive-date=11 February 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref name=\"SHGDPKG\">[http://www.china.org.cn/english/2003/Feb/54962.htm Shanghai's GDP Keeps Growing] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050830103443/http://www.china.org.cn/english/2003/Feb/54962.htm |date=30 August 2005 }} Xinhua News Agency 1 February 2003.</ref>\n\n====Steel industry====\n{{main|Steel industry in China}}\n[[File:Tianjin Skyline 2009 Sep 11 by Nangua 1.jpg|thumb|Skyscrapers of [[Tianjin]]]]\nIn 2018, China was the largest producer of steel in the world, accounting for more than 50% of the world's steel<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.trade.gov/steel/countries/pdfs/exports-china.pdf|title=Steel Exports Report: China|website=US Department of Commerce|access-date=}}</ref> In 2018, China produced 928 million&nbsp;tons of steel, an increase of almost 100% from 2008.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-17/china-s-steel-machine-revs-up-to-record-to-feed-infrastructure|title=China Is Producing More Steel Than Ever|date=17 April 2019|access-date=22 June 2019|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623005347/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-04-17/china-s-steel-machine-revs-up-to-record-to-feed-infrastructure|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> 6 of 10 of largest steel producers in the world are in China. Profits are low despite continued high demand due to high debt and overproduction of high end products produced with the equipment financed by the high debt. The central government is aware of this problem but there is no easy way to resolve it as local governments strongly support local steel production. Meanwhile, each firm aggressively increases production.<ref name=\"NYTSteel2012\">{{cite news |title=In China's Floundering Steel Sector, the Burden of Politics |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/business/global/in-chinas-floundering-steel-sector-the-burden-of-politics.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=3 May 2012 |agency=Reuters |accessdate=4 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120505212532/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/04/business/global/in-chinas-floundering-steel-sector-the-burden-of-politics.html |archive-date=5 May 2012 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[Iron ore]] production kept pace with steel production in the early 1990s but was soon outpaced by imported iron ore and other metals in the early 2000s. Steel production, an estimated 140&nbsp;million&nbsp;tons in 2000 increased to 419&nbsp;million&nbsp;tons in 2006 and 928 million tons by 2018. Much of the country's steel output comes from a large number of small-scale producing centers, one of the largest being [[Anshan]] in [[Liaoning]].\n\nChina was the top exporter of steel in the world in 2018; export volumes in 2018 were 66.9&nbsp;million&nbsp;tons, a 9% decrease over the previous year.<ref>[http://english.people.com.cn/90001/6590861.html Steel exports fall in 2008&nbsp;\u2013 People's Daily Online] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091102151634/http://english.people.com.cn/90001/6590861.html |date=2 November 2009 }}. English.people.com.cn (12 February 2009). Retrieved on 6 August 2010.</ref> The decline slowed China's decade-old steel export growth. As of 2012 steel exports faced widespread [[Dumping (pricing policy)|anti-dumping taxes]] and had not returned to pre-2008 levels. However, in 2015, China's steel exports reached a record high of 110 million metric tons.<ref name=\":0\" /> Domestic demand remained strong, particularly in the developing west where steel production in [[Xinjiang]] was expanding.<ref name=NYTSteel2012 />\n\nOn 26 April 2012, a warning was issued by China's bank regulator to use caution with respect to lending money to steel companies who, as profits from the manufacture and sale of steel have fallen, have sometimes used borrowed money for speculative purposes. According to the China Iron and Steel Association the Chinese steel industry lost 1 billion Rmb in the first quarter of 2012, its first loss since 2000.<ref name=\"FTWarning\">{{cite news |title=China warns on lending to steel plants|url=http://www.ft.com/intl/cms/s/0/12763b2c-ae29-11e1-b842-00144feabdc0.html |newspaper=Financial Times |date=4 June 2012 |author=Simon Rabinovitch |author2=Leslie Hook |accessdate=4 June 2012}}</ref> For the year 2018, China's steel industry reported profits of CNY 470 billion ($70 billion), which was 39% higher than the year before.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://steelguru.com/steel/China%20steel%20industry%20sees%20profits%20in%202018%20up%2039pct/533252?type=steel|title=China steel industry sees profits in 2018 up 39pct|last=admin@steelguru.com|website=SteelGuru India|language=en|access-date=23 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n====Automotive industry====\n{{main|Automotive industry in China}}\n\nChina is the world's largest automobile producer, manufacturing more than 27 million vehicles in 2018\u2014for comparison, the corresponding numbers for the US and Japan were 11.3 million and 9.7 million respectively. By 2006 China had become the world's third largest automotive vehicle manufacturer (after US and Japan) and the second largest consumer (only after the US). However, four years later, in 2010, China was manufacturing more vehicles than the U.S. and Japan combined. [[Automobile]] manufacturing has soared during the reform period. In 1975 only 139,800 automobiles were produced annually, but by 1985 production had reached 443,377, then jumped to nearly 1.1&nbsp;million by 1992 and increased fairly evenly each year up until 2001, when it reached 2.3&nbsp;million. In 2002 production rose to nearly 3.25&nbsp;million and then jumped to 4.44&nbsp;million in 2003, 5.07&nbsp;million in 2004, 5.71&nbsp;million in 2005, 7.28&nbsp;million in 2006, 8.88&nbsp;million in 2007, 9.35&nbsp;million in 2008 and 13.83&nbsp;million in 2009. China has become the number-one automaker in the world in 2009. Domestic sales have kept pace with production. After respectable annual increases in the mid- and late 1990s, passenger car sales soared in the early 2000s. In 2006, a total of 7.22&nbsp;million automobiles were sold, including 5.18&nbsp;million units of passenger cars and 2&nbsp;million units of commercial vehicles.\n\nIn 2010, China became the world's largest automotive vehicle manufacturer as well as the largest consumer ahead of the [[United States]] with an estimated 18 million new cars sold.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-10/china-2010-auto-sales-reach-18-million-extend-lead-update1-.html |title=China 2010 Auto Sales Reach 18 Million, Extend Lead |publisher=Bloomberg |date=10 January 2011 |accessdate=27 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110622215636/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-01-10/china-2010-auto-sales-reach-18-million-extend-lead-update1-.html |archive-date=22 June 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref> However, new car sales grew only by an estimated 1% between 2011 and 2012 due to the escalation in the [[Spratly Islands dispute]], which involved [[Japan]], the world's third largest producer of vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gasnier |first=Matt |url=http://bestsellingcarsblog.com/2013/02/16/world-2012-the-20-biggest-car-markets-thailand-shoots-up/ |title=World 2012 \u2013 The 20 biggest car markets: Thailand shoots up! |publisher=bestsellingcarsblog.com |date=16 February 2013 |accessdate=16 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130219034221/http://bestsellingcarsblog.com/2013/02/16/world-2012-the-20-biggest-car-markets-thailand-shoots-up/ |archive-date=19 February 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nChina's automotive industry has been so successful that it began exporting car parts in 1999. China began to plan major moves into the automobile and components export business starting in 2005. A new [[Honda]] factory in [[Guangzhou]] was built in 2004 solely for the export market and was expected to ship 30,000 passenger vehicles to Europe in 2005. By 2004, 12 major foreign automotive manufacturers had [[joint-venture]] plants in China. They produced a wide range of automobiles, [[minivan]]s, [[sport utility vehicle]]s, [[bus]]es, and [[truck]]s. In 2003 China exported US$4.7&nbsp;billion worth of vehicles and components. The vehicle export was 78,000 units in 2004, 173,000 units in 2005, and 340,000 units in 2006. The vehicle and component export is targeted to reach US$70&nbsp;billion by 2010.\n\nThe market for domestically produced cars, under a local name, is likely to continue to grow both inside China and outside. Companies such as Geely, Qiantu and Chery are constantly evaluating new international locations, both in developing and developed countries.<ref>Alon, Ilan, Marc Fetscherin, Marc Sardy (2008), \"Geely Motors: A Chinese Automaker Enters International Markets\", ''International Journal of Chinese Culture and Management'', 1 (4), 489\u2013498.</ref>\n\n==== Electric Car Industry ====\n[[File:Byd duel mode engine.jpg|thumb| [[BYD Auto|BYD]] Dual Mode hybrid engine]]\nChina is also the world's No. 1 manufacturer of electric cars, producing about 1.3 million new energy vehicles in 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2019/02/china-is-winning-the-electric-vehicle-race/|title=China is winning the electric vehicle race|website=World Economic Forum|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190621210527/https://www.weforum.org/agenda/2019/02/china-is-winning-the-electric-vehicle-race/|archive-date=21 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> China has been No. 1 in the world in production of electric vehicles since 2015. China also buys half of all the electric cars in the world,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1552991/china-buys-one-out-of-every-two-electric-vehicles-sold-globally/|title=China buys one out of every two electric vehicles sold globally|last=Huang|first=Echo|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605083607/https://qz.com/1552991/china-buys-one-out-of-every-two-electric-vehicles-sold-globally/|archive-date=5 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> since Chinese brands account for about 96% of electric cars sold in China.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaeldunne/2018/03/30/chinas-electric-vehicle-leaders-who-are-they/|title=China's Electric Vehicle Leaders \u2013 Who Are They?|last=Dunne|first=Michael J.|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623094138/https://www.forbes.com/sites/michaeldunne/2018/03/30/chinas-electric-vehicle-leaders-who-are-they/|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> China has now more than 100 EV manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://qz.com/1517557/five-things-to-know-about-chinas-electric-car-boom/|title=Five things to know about China's electric-car boom|last=Rathi|first=Akshat|website=Quartz|language=en|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623005937/https://qz.com/1517557/five-things-to-know-about-chinas-electric-car-boom/|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> BYD, Beijing Electric Vehicle Corp,\u00a0Byton, BAIC, Changjiang EV, Great Wall Motors, Kandi, Lifan Motors, NIO, ZhiDou, Shanghai Auto and Zotye are the major Chinese EV brands and manufacturers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mashable.com/2018/04/25/china-electric-vehicles-tesla-beijing-auto-show/|title=9 companies trying to be the 'Tesla of China'|last=Lekach|first=Sasha|website=Mashable|language=en|access-date=23 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190623005939/https://mashable.com/2018/04/25/china-electric-vehicles-tesla-beijing-auto-show/|archive-date=23 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Other industries====\n{{further|Telecommunications industry in China|Electronics industry in China|Pharmaceutical industry in China|Defense industry in China|Shipping industry in China}}\nSubstantial investments were made in the manufacture of [[solar panel]]s and [[wind generator]]s by a number of companies, supported by liberal loans by banks and local governments. However, by 2012 manufacturing capacity had far outstripped domestic and global demand for both products, particularly solar panels, which were subjected to anti-dumping penalties by both the United States and Europe. The global oversupply has resulted in bankruptcies and production cutbacks both inside and outside China. China has budgeted $50 billion to subsidize production of solar power over the two decades following 2015 but, even at the sharply reduced price resulting from oversupply, as of 2012 cost of solar power in China remained three times that of power produced by conventional coal-fired power plants.<ref name=\"NYT10412\">{{cite news|title=Glut of Solar Panels Poses a New Threat to China|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/05/business/global/glut-of-solar-panels-is-a-new-test-for-china.html|accessdate=5 October 2012|newspaper=The New York Times|date=4 October 2012|author=Keith Bradsher|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121005074556/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/10/05/business/global/glut-of-solar-panels-is-a-new-test-for-china.html|archive-date=5 October 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n[[File:XiAn qujiang.jpg|thumb|340px|Tang Paradise at night]]\nChina is the world's biggest sex toy producer and accounts for 70% of the worldwide sex toys production.<ref name=\"sex-toy\">{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2010-07/10/content_10090553.htm|title=Nation becomes world's biggest sex-toy producer|author=China Daily|date=10 July 2010|accessdate=11 July 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100915045156/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2010-07/10/content_10090553.htm|archivedate=15 September 2010}}</ref> In the country, 1,000 manufacturers are active in this industry, which generates about two billion dollars a year.<ref name=\"sex-toy\"/>\n\nAs of 2011, China was the world's largest market for personal computers<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111903461304576525852486131230?mod=googlenews_wsj | work=The Wall Street Journal | first=Owen | last=Fletcher | title=China Passes U.S. as World's Biggest PC Market | date=24 August 2011 | access-date=3 August 2017 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170923095604/https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424053111903461304576525852486131230?mod=googlenews_wsj | archive-date=23 September 2017 | url-status=live }}</ref> Since 2019, Samsung Electronics, Hyundai Motors, Kia Motors and LG Electronics are moving some or all production out of China, in order to reduce overdependence on the Chinese market and avoid risks related with increased local competition, China's economic slowdown and the [[US-China trade war]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://asia.nikkei.com/Business/Business-trends/South-Korean-companies-shift-production-out-of-China|title=South Korean companies shift production out of China|website=Nikkei Asian Review}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techtimes.com/articles/220321/20180205/lg-exits-china-smartphone-market-because-it-just-cant-compete-with-local-brands.htm|title=LG Exits China Smartphone Market Because It Just Can't Compete With Local Brands|first=Tech|last=Times|date=5 February 2018|website=Tech Times}}</ref>\n\n===Services===\nThe output of China's [[Service sector|services]] in 2015 [[List of countries by GDP sector composition|ranks second]] worldwide after the United States. High power and telecom density has ensured that the country has remained on a high-growth trajectory over the long term. In 2015 the services sector produced 52.9% of China's annual GDP, second only to manufacturing. However, its proportion of GDP is still low compared to the ratio in more developed countries, and the [[Agriculture in China|agricultural sector]] still employs a larger workforce.\n\nPrior to the onset of economic reforms in 1978, China's services sector was characterized by state-operated [[Retailing|shops]], [[rationing]], and regulated prices\u2014with reform came private markets, individual entrepreneurs, and a commercial sector. The [[wholesale]] and [[retail]] trade has expanded quickly, with numerous [[shopping mall]]s, retail shops, restaurant chains and hotels constructed in urban areas. [[Public administration]] remains a main component of the service sector, while [[Tourism in China|tourism]] has become a significant factor in [[employment]] and a source of [[foreign exchange reserves|foreign exchange]].<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Alon|editor1-first=Ilan|title=Chinese Economic Transition and International Marketing Strategy|date=2003|publisher=Praeger|location=Westport, Conn.|isbn=9781567205879|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hHvAi53-F8cC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|access-date=11 November 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624043507/https://books.google.com/books?id=hHvAi53-F8cC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q&f=false|archive-date=24 June 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Telecommunications====\n{{main|Telecommunications in China}}\nChina possesses a diversified [[communications]] system that links all parts of the country by Internet, telephone, telegraph, radio, and television.\n\nChina's number of Internet users or [[netizens]] topped 137&nbsp;million by the end of 2006,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.chinadaily.net/china/2007-01/24/content_790804.htm |title=Internet users to log in at world No.1 |work= China Daily |date= 24 January 2007 |accessdate=28 February 2012}}</ref> an increase of 23.4% from a year before and 162&nbsp;million by June 2007, making China the second-largest Internet user after the United States, according to China's [[Ministry of Industry and Information Technology of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Information Industry]] (MII). China's mobile phone penetration rate was 34% in 2007. In 2006, mobile phone users sent 429&nbsp;billion text messages (on average 967 text messages per user). For 2006, the number of [[landline|fixed-lines]] grew by 79%, mainly in the rural areas.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/7140300.stm \"Emerging giants spur telecom boom\"], BBC News, {{Nowrap|12 December}} 2007.</ref>\n\n====Tourism====\n{{main|Tourism in China}}\nChina's [[tourism industry]] is one of the fastest-growing industries in the national economy and is also one of the industries with a very distinct global competitive edge. According to the [[World Travel and Tourism Council]], travel and tourism directly contributed CNY 1,362 billion (US$216 billion) to the Chinese economy (about 2.6% of GDP).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184218/http://wttc.org/site_media/uploads/downloads/china2013.pdf \"China Travel & Tourism Economic Impact Report\"] (2013), [[World Travel and Tourism Council]].</ref> In 2011, total international tourist arrivals was 58 million, and international tourism receipts were US$48 billion.<ref>[http://dtxtq4w60xqpw.cloudfront.net/sites/all/files/pdf/unwto_highlights13_en_lr.pdf \"UNWTO Tourism Highlights\"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130718115306/http://dtxtq4w60xqpw.cloudfront.net/sites/all/files/pdf/unwto_highlights13_en_lr.pdf |date=18 July 2013 }}, [[World Tourism Organization]], 2013.</ref>\n\nDomestic tourism market makes up more than 90% of the country's tourism traffic, and contributes more than 70% of total tourism revenue. In 2002, domestic tourists reached 878&nbsp;million and tourism revenue was $46.9&nbsp;billion. A large middle class with strong consumption power is emerging in China, especially in major cities. China's outbound tourists reached 20.22&nbsp;million in 2003, overtaking Japan for the first time.\n\nIt is forecast by the [[World Tourism Organization]] that China's tourism industry will take up to 8.6% of world market share to become the world's top tourism industry by 2020.\n\nChinese [[business travel]] spending is also forecast to be the highest in the world by 2014, overtaking the United States. According to a Global Business Travel Association study, total business-travel spending is expected to reach US$195 billion in 2012.<ref>{{cite news| title=Continued growth in Chinese business travel next year: GBTA study| url=http://www.ttgmice.com/index.php/magazine/?term_id&issues&ID=31105| newspaper=TTGmice| date=October 2012| accessdate=9 November 2012}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIt is forecast by Euromonitor International that China will overtake [[France]] as the leading travel destination by 2030.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/Euromonitor/status/1059453533962096640|title=Euromonitor on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=11 November 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n====Luxury goods====\n{{main|Luxury goods of China}}\nLuxury spending in China has skyrocketed, an indicator of the country's newfound wealth. For example, the Chinese [[bottled water]] industry is forecast to more than double in size in 2008, becoming a $10.5 billion industry. Meanwhile, as those who once had no recourse but low-quality [[tap water]] take advantage of its availability in supermarkets, those who had little or no running water are now capitalizing on its availability. Tap water production and supply is expected to grow by 29.3% in 2008, to $11.9&nbsp;billion. China's [[Automotive industry in China|automotive industry]] is expected to expand by 29.5% to nearly $200&nbsp;billion. Also, consumption of chocolate and other confectionery is to increase by 24.3%, as the industry expands to $4.6&nbsp;billion. Additionally China's [[fast food]] industry has been growing at a 20.8% annual rate. The [[LVMH Group]], who own brands including [[Louis Vuitton]] apparel, [[Mo\u00ebt & Chandon]] wines and champagne and [[Hennessy]] cognacs, reported earnings growth of over 25% in 2007 in China, with the country accounting for around 16% of LVMH's global business.<ref>[http://www.ibisworld.com/newsletter/issues/us/08mar/news.htm: \"China&nbsp;\u2013 Let the Good Times Roll\"], ''IBISWorld Newsletter'', March 2008</ref>\n\nAfter an October 2012 ban on government agencies purchasing luxury goods, often used as \"gifts\", sales of [[luxury goods of China|luxury goods in China]] remained strong but slowed, even falling slightly for some luxury retailers in the 4th quarter of 2012,<ref name=\"Caixin022613\">{{cite news |title=China's Frills and Posh Market Springs a Leak: Wealthy Chinese consumers continue to drive global demand for luxury goods, but the engine is losing steam |url=http://english.caixin.com/2013-02-26/100494654.html |publisher=Caixin |date=26 February 2013 |author=Qu Yunxu |accessdate=26 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130302030136/http://english.caixin.com/2013-02-26/100494654.html |archive-date=2 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> with sales of [[Shark fin soup|shark fin]]s and [[Edible bird's nest|edible swallow nest]]s (once staples of lavish government banquets) down sharply.<ref name=\"NYT032713\">{{cite news|title=Elite in China Face Austerity Under Xi's Rule|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/28/world/asia/xi-jinping-imposes-austerity-measures-on-chinas-elite.html|newspaper=The New York Times|date=27 March 2013|author=Andrew Jacobs|accessdate=28 March 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328095140/http://www.nytimes.com/2013/03/28/world/asia/xi-jinping-imposes-austerity-measures-on-chinas-elite.html|archive-date=28 March 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRetail sales in China account for only 7% of global retail sales; however, Chinese buyers account for 25% of global retail sales of luxury consumer goods. Many shops in international travel destinations have specialized staff devoted to Chinese customers.<ref name=Caixin022613 />\n\n====Cybercrime====\nAs of 2016, [[Cybercrime|computer crime]] is a lucrative illicit practice in China. An academic study released in August 2012 by the [[University of California]] (UC) [[UC Institute on Global Conflict and Cooperation|Institute on Global Conflict and Cooperation]], claimed that China's \"cyber [[black market]]\" involved over 90,000 participants, cost the local economy 5.36 billion yuan ([[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]536m), negatively impacted upon 110 million internet users (22%), and affected 1.1 million websites (20%) in 2011.<ref>{{cite news |title=Exposing China's vast underground economy |url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/08/18/baidu_tencent_used_by_chinese_cyber_crims/?page=2 |newspaper=The Register |date=18 August 2012 |author=Phil Muncaster |accessdate=25 September 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929051229/http://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/08/18/baidu_tencent_used_by_chinese_cyber_crims/?page=2 |archive-date=29 September 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> In July 2012, China's [[State Council of the People's Republic of China|State Council]] released a set of [[information security]] guidelines as a measure to combat [[cyber crime]] that included increased auditing, security reporting, and monitoring, and a commitment to \"reduce the number of internet connection points\".<ref>{{cite news|title=China lays out glorious eight-point infosec masterplan|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/07/19/china_government_cyber_security_guidelines|newspaper=The Register|date=19 July 2012|author=Phil Muncaster|accessdate=25 September 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130929051325/http://www.theregister.co.uk/2012/07/19/china_government_cyber_security_guidelines/|archive-date=29 September 2013|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Labour and welfare==\n{{main|Labor relations in China|Social welfare in China}}\n[[File:Shanghaid02.jpg|thumb|A window washer on a skyscraper in [[Shanghai]]]]\n[[File:20040906yunankama.jpg|thumb|Labor makes ceramics in [[Yunnan]]]]\n[[File:Alley with miner.jpg|thumb|A Chinese coal miner at the [[Jin Hua Gong Mine]]]]\nOne of the hallmarks of China's socialist economy was its promise of employment to all able and willing to work and job-security with virtually lifelong tenure. This socialist policy is known as the [[iron rice bowl]].\n\nIn 1979\u20131980, the state reformed factories by giving wage increases to workers, which was immediately offset by sharply rising [[inflation]] rates of 6\u20137%. The reforms also dismantled the [[iron rice bowl]], which meant it witnessed a rise in unemployment in the economy. In 1979\u201380 there were 20&nbsp;million unemployed people.<ref>Vice-Premier [[Li Xiannian]]'s speech, published in the [[Hong Kong newspaper]] ''Ming Pao'' on 14 June 1979.</ref>\n\n<imagemap>Image: China employment by economic sectors.png|thumb|left|This chart show the Chinese employment by sectors during time<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20141117072912/http://www.bluenomics.com/data#!data/labour_market/employment_by_sectors/employment_by_broad_economic_sectors/employment_by_broad_economic_sectors_annual_of_tot_empl_%7Cchart/line$countries=china&sorting=list//title \"Labour Market Employment By Sectors\"].</ref></imagemap>\nChina's estimated employed labor force in 2005 totaled 791&nbsp;million persons, about 60% of the total population. During 2003, 49% of the labor force worked in [[agriculture]], [[forestry]], and [[fishing]]; 22% in [[mining]], [[manufacturing]], [[energy]], and [[construction]] industries; and 29% in the [[Tertiary sector of economic activity|services]] sector and other categories. In 2004 some 25&nbsp;million persons were employed by 743,000 [[private enterprise]]s. Urban wages rose rapidly from 2004 to 2007, at a rate of 13 to 19% per year with average wages near $200/month in 2007.<ref>[http://www.stats.gov.cn/english/newsandcomingevents/t20071029_402440482.htm \"Average Wage of On-Duty Staff and Workers in Urban Areas Jumped in the First Three Quarters\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100717232344/http://www.stats.gov.cn/english/newsandcomingevents/t20071029_402440482.htm |date=17 July 2010 }}. [[National Bureau of Statistics of China]].\u30002007-10-29, 15:35:2.</ref> By 2016 the average monthly wage for workers engaged in manufacturing goods for export was $424. This wage, combined with other costs of doing business in China, had, more or less, equalized any Chinese cost advantage with respect to developed economies.<ref name=\"NYT72216\">{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Schuman |title=Is China Stealing Jobs? It May Be Losing Them, Instead |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/23/business/international/china-jobs-donald-trump.html |work=The New York Times |date=22 July 2016 |access-date=23 July 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160724050641/http://www.nytimes.com/2016/07/23/business/international/china-jobs-donald-trump.html |archive-date=24 July 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nThe [[All-China Federation of Trade Unions]] (ACFTU) was established in 1925 to represent the interests of national and local [[trade union]]s and trade union councils. The ACFTU reported a membership of 130&nbsp;million, out of an estimated 248&nbsp;million urban workers, at the end of 2002. Chinese trade unions are organized on a broad industrial basis. Membership is open to those who rely on [[wage]]s for the whole or a large part of their [[income]], a qualification that excludes most agricultural workers.\n\nIn 2010, the issues of manufacturing wages caused a strike at a Honda parts plant. This resulted in wage increases both at the struck plant and other industrial plants.<ref>[http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9FVQT4O0.htm \"Honda suspends production in China due to strike\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100529102157/http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D9FVQT4O0.htm |date=29 May 2010 }} [[Associated Press]] article on Businessweek.com, 28 May 2010</ref><ref>Keith Bradsher (28 May 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/29/business/global/29strikeside.html \"Workers Squeezing Honda With Especially Costly Strike\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160723022636/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/29/business/global/29strikeside.html |date=23 July 2016 }} ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref><ref>Keith Bradsher and David Barboza (28 May 2010), [https://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/29/business/global/29honda.html \"Strike in China Highlights Gap in Workers' Pay\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170113044749/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/05/29/business/global/29honda.html |date=13 January 2017 }}, ''[[The New York Times]]''</ref><ref>[http://www2.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2010-05/28/content_9903694.htm \"Honda's China plants halt production as workers strike for higher salaries\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607031415/http://www2.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2010-05/28/content_9903694.htm |date=7 June 2011 }} [[Xinhua]] article in ''[[China Daily]]'' updated: 28 May 2010 09:42</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/02/business/global/02foxconn.html \"Foxconn Raises Worker Pay 30%\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225132633/http://www.nytimes.com/2010/06/02/business/global/02foxconn.html |date=25 February 2017 }} article from Bloomberg News printed in ''[[The New York Times]]'' 1 June 2010</ref>\n\nThe 2010 census found that China was now half urban and rapidly aging due to the one child policy. This is expected to lead to increased demand for labor to take care of an elderly population and a reduced supply of migrant labor from the countryside.<ref>[http://english.aljazeera.net/news/asia-pacific/2011/04/201142852019929352.html \"China is ageing and growing more slowly\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110428112636/http://english.aljazeera.net//news/asia-pacific/2011/04/201142852019929352.html |date=28 April 2011 }}. ''Al Jazeera'', 28 April 2011.</ref>\n\nDue to worsening pollution, the corruption and political uncertainties of the one-party state and the limited economic freedom in an economy dominated by large state-owned enterprises, many skilled professionals are either leaving the country or preparing safety nets for themselves abroad.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/chinas-millionaire-exodus-as-wealthy-flee-with-america-the-preferred-destination-9069551.html |title=China's millionaire exodus as wealthy flee with America the preferred destination |last=Boren |first=Zachary |date=18 January 2014 |work=The Independent |location=London |accessdate=14 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140915072540/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/chinas-millionaire-exodus-as-wealthy-flee-with-america-the-preferred-destination-9069551.html |archive-date=15 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20140212000018&cid=1103&MainCatID=0 |title=Pollution sees middle, upper class exodus from China's major cities |date=12 February 2014 |accessdate=11 February 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140221225619/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20140212000018&cid=1103&MainCatID=0 |archive-date=21 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>Johnson, Ian. [https://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/01/world/asia/wary-of-future-many-professionals-leave-china.html?pagewanted=all \"Wary of Future, Professionals Leave China in Record Numbers\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170225132236/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/11/01/world/asia/wary-of-future-many-professionals-leave-china.html?pagewanted=all |date=25 February 2017 }}. ''[[NYT]]'', 31 October 2012.</ref> In the decade up to 2014, 10 million Chinese emigrated to other countries, taking assets and their technical skills.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20140123000098&cid=1103&MainCatID=0 |title=Migration gap in China alarming: report |date=23 January 2014 |work=Want China Times |accessdate=23 January 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201184548/http://www.wantchinatimes.com/news-subclass-cnt.aspx?id=20140123000098&cid=1103&MainCatID=0 |archive-date=1 February 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref> Perceived corruption continued to grow worse in China as it dropped from 75th to 80th place in Transparency International's index of state corruption.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/china/2012/china-121205-voa02.htm|title=China Earns Poor Score on Corruption Index|author=Pike, John|publisher=globalsecurity.org|access-date=6 December 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121226213909/http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/china/2012/china-121205-voa02.htm|archive-date=26 December 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA law approved February 2013 will mandate a nationwide minimum wage at 40% average urban salaries to be phased in fully by 2015.<ref name=bbcmw>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21347819 \"China promises rise in minimum wage to close income gap\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171127222220/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/business-21347819 |date=27 November 2017 }} BBC News, 6 February 2013</ref>\n\n==External trade==\n{{main|History of trade of the People's Republic of China}}{{Further|List of the largest trading partners of China|List of exports of China|List of Chinese administrative divisions by exports|China\u2013United States trade war}}\n[[File:2006Chinese exports.PNG|thumb|300px|Global distribution of Chinese exports in 2006 as a percentage of the top market]]\n[[International trade]] makes up a sizeable portion of China's overall economy. Being a [[Second World]] country at the time{{When|date=December 2019}}, a meaningful segment of China's trade with the [[Third World]] was financed through grants, credits, and other forms of assistance. The principal efforts were made in Asia, especially to [[Indonesia]], [[Myanmar]], Pakistan, and [[Sri Lanka]], but large loans were also granted in Africa ([[Ghana]], [[Algeria]], [[Tanzania]]) and in the Middle East ([[Egypt]]). However, after [[Mao Zedong]]'s death in 1976, these efforts were scaled back. After which, trade with developing countries became negligible, though during that time, [[Hong Kong]] and [[Taiwan]] both began to emerge as major trading partners.\n\nSince economic reforms began in the late 1970s, China sought to decentralize its foreign trade system to integrate itself into the international trading system. In November 1991, China joined the [[Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation]] (APEC) group, which promotes [[free trade]] and cooperation in the economic, trade, investment, and technology spheres. China served as APEC chair in 2001, and Shanghai hosted the annual APEC leaders meeting in October of that year.\n\nAfter reaching a bilateral WTO agreement with the EU and other trading partners in summer 2000, China worked on a multilateral WTO accession package. China concluded multilateral negotiations on its accession to the WTO in September 2001. The completion of its accession protocol and Working Party Report paved the way for its entry into the WTO on 11 December 2001, after 16 years of negotiations, the longest in the history of the [[General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade]]. However, U.S. exporters continue to have concerns about fair market access due to China's restrictive trade policies and U.S. export restrictions. In October 2019, Chinese Vice Premier Han Zheng promised to further decrease tariffs and remove non-tariff barriers for global investors, he also welcomed multinational companies to invest more in China.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-tariff-reduce-idUSKBN1WY08M|title=China to further reduce tariffs and remove non-tariff barriers for foreign investors: Xinhua|date=19 October 2019|work=Reuters|access-date=19 October 2019|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191019135448/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-tariff-reduce-idUSKBN1WY08M|archive-date=19 October 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Jawaharlal Nehru Trust Port.jpg|thumb|With bilateral trade exceeding US$38.6&nbsp;billion, China is India's largest trading partner<ref>[http://news.tootoo.com/Industry_News/Latest_News/20080325/79764.html China emerges India's top trade partner] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080907234848/http://news.tootoo.com/Industry_News/Latest_News/20080325/79764.html |date=7 September 2008 }}. News.tootoo.com (25 March 2008). Retrieved on 6 August 2010.</ref> and shown here is a Chinese container ship unloading its cargo at [[Jawaharlal Nehru Port]], [[Navi Mumbai]], India]]\nChina's global trade exceeded $4.16&nbsp;trillion at the end of 2013. It first broke the $100&nbsp;billion mark in 1988, $200&nbsp;billion in 1994, $500&nbsp;billion in 2001, $1&nbsp;trillion mark ($1.15&nbsp;trillion) in 2004,$2&nbsp;trillion mark ($2.17&nbsp;trillion) in 2007,$3&nbsp;trillion mark ($3.64&nbsp;trillion) in 2011, and $4&nbsp;trillion mark ($4.16&nbsp;trillion) in 2013. The table below shows the average annual growth (in nominal US&nbsp;dollar terms) of China's foreign trade during the reform era.\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Period\n!Two-way trade||Exports||Imports\n|-\n|1981\u20131985||+12.8%||+8.6%||+16.1%\n|-\n|1986\u20131990||+10.6%||+17.8%||+4.8%\n|-\n|1991\u20131995||+19.5%||+19.1%||+19.9%\n|-\n|1996\u20132000||+11.0%||+10.9%||+11.3%\n|-\n|2001\u20132005||+24.6%||+25.0%||+24.0%\n|-\n|2006\u20132010||+15.9%||+15.7%||+16.1%\n|-\n|2015||\u22128.0%||\u22122.8%||\u221214.1%\n|}\n[[File:United States Balance of Trade Deficit-pie chart.svg|thumb|U.S. trade deficit (in billions, goods only) by country in 2014]]\n\nThe vast majority of China's imports consists of industrial supplies and capital goods, notably machinery and high-technology equipment, the majority of which comes from the developed countries, primarily Japan{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}} and the United States{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}. Regionally, almost half of China's imports come from East and Southeast Asia, and about one-fourth of China's exports go to the same destinations{{Citation needed|date=March 2009}}. About 80 percent of China's exports consist of manufactured goods, most of which are textiles and electronic equipment, with agricultural products and chemicals constituting the remainder. Out of the five busiest [[port]]s in the world, three are in China. The U.S. trade deficit with China reached $233&nbsp;billion in 2006, as imports grew 18%. China's share of total U.S. imports has grown from 7% to 15% since 1996.\n\nTrade volume between China and Russia reached $29.1&nbsp;billion in 2005, an increase of 37.1% compared with 2004. A spokesman for the [[Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Commerce]], Van Jingsun, said that the volume of trade between China and Russia could exceed 40 billion dollars in 2007.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trade between China and Russia could exceed $40 bln in 2007|publisher=The Voice of Russia|date=2 August 2007|url=http://www.ruvr.ru/main.php?lng=eng&q=14378&cid=46&p=02.08.2007|access-date=4 August 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927152209/http://www.ruvr.ru/main.php?lng=eng&q=14378&cid=46&p=02.08.2007|archive-date=27 September 2007|url-status=live}}</ref> China's export of machinery and electronic goods to Russia grew 70%, which is 24% of China's total export to Russia in the first 11&nbsp;months of 2005. During the same time, China's export of high-tech products to Russia increased by 58%, and that is 7% of China's total exports to Russia. Also at that time period, border trade between the two countries reached $5.13&nbsp;billion, growing 35% and accounting for nearly 20% of the total trade. Most of China's exports to Russia remain apparel and footwear. Russia is China's eighth largest trade partner and China is now Russia's fourth largest trade partner, and China now has over 750 investment projects in Russia, involving $1.05&nbsp;billion. China's contracted investment in Russia totaled $368&nbsp;million during January\u2013September 2005, twice that in 2004.\n\n[[File:E7210-NN-kitaj-auto.jpg|thumb|Chinese cars at a dealer's lot in [[Nizhny Novgorod]], the traditional capital of the Russian automotive industry]]\nChinese imports from Russia are mainly those of energy sources, such as crude oil, which is mostly transported by rail, and electricity exports from neighboring Siberian and Far Eastern regions. In the near future, exports of both of these commodities are set to increase, as Russia is building the [[Eastern Siberia-Pacific Ocean oil pipeline]] with a branch going to the Chinese border, and Russian power grid monopoly UES is building some of its hydropower stations with a view of future exports to China.\n\nExport growth has continued to be a major component supporting China's rapid economic growth. To increase exports, China pursued policies such as fostering the rapid development of foreign-invested factories, which assembled imported components into consumer goods for export and liberalizing trading rights. In its [[Eleventh Five-Year Plan (People's Republic of China)|11th Five-Year Program]], adopted in 2005, China placed greater emphasis on developing a consumer demand-driven economy to sustain economic growth and address imbalances.\n\n==Foreign investment==\n{{see also|Foreign Investment Law of the People's Republic of China|Qualified Domestic Institutional Investor|Qualified Foreign Institutional Investor|China Investment Promotion Agency|China Council for the Promotion of International Trade|Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China}}\nChina's investment climate has changed dramatically with more than two decades of reform. In the early 1980s, China restricted foreign investments to export-oriented operations and required foreign investors to form joint-venture partnerships with Chinese firms. The [[Encouraged Industry Catalogue]] sets out the degree of foreign involvement allowed in various industry sectors. From the beginning of the reforms legalizing foreign investment, capital inflows expanded every year until 1999.<ref>China Statistical Yearbook 2007, Table 18-14: http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/ndsj/2007/indexeh.htm {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220113912/http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/ndsj/2007/indexeh.htm |date=20 December 2008 }}</ref> Foreign-invested enterprises account for 58\u201360% of China's imports and exports.<ref>China Statistical Yearbook 2007, Table 18-13: http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/ndsj/2007/indexeh.htm {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081220113912/http://www.stats.gov.cn/tjsj/ndsj/2007/indexeh.htm |date=20 December 2008 }}</ref>\n\nSince the early 1990s, the government has allowed foreign investors to manufacture and sell a wide range of goods on the domestic market, eliminated time restrictions on the establishment of joint ventures, provided some assurances against [[nationalization]], allowed foreign partners to become chairs of [[joint venture]] boards, and authorized the establishment of wholly foreign-owned enterprises, now the preferred form of FDI. In 1991, China granted more preferential tax treatment for [[Wholly Foreign Owned Enterprise]]s and contractual ventures and for foreign companies, which invested in selected economic zones or in projects encouraged by the state, such as energy, communications and transportation.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}}\n\nChina also authorized some foreign banks to open branches in [[Shanghai]] and allowed foreign investors to purchase special \"B\" shares of [[stock]] in selected companies listed on the [[Shanghai Stock Exchange|Shanghai]] and [[Shenzhen Stock Exchange|Shenzhen]] Securities Exchanges. These \"B\" shares sold to foreigners carried no ownership rights in a company. In 1997, China approved 21,046 foreign investment projects and received over $45&nbsp;billion in [[foreign direct investment]]. China revised significantly its laws on Wholly Foreign-Owned Enterprises and China Foreign Equity Joint Ventures in 2000 and 2001, easing export performance and domestic content requirements.{{citation needed|date=December 2014}} The Vice Minister of Finance Zhu Guangyao announced, foreign investors will be allowed to own up to 51% on domestic financial service companies. Formerly foreign ownership was limited to a 49% stake in these firms.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faz.net/1.5285864|title=\u00d6ffnung des Finanzmarktes: Ausl\u00e4nder d\u00fcrfen Mehrheit an chinesischen Banken \u00fcbernehmen|via=www.faz.net}}</ref>\n\nForeign investment remains a strong element in China's rapid expansion in world trade and has been an important factor in the growth of urban jobs. In 1998, foreign-invested enterprises produced about 40% of China's exports, and foreign exchange reserves totalled about $145&nbsp;billion. Foreign-invested enterprises today produce about half of China's exports (the majority of China's foreign investment come from [[Hong Kong]], [[Macau]] and [[Taiwan]]), and China continues to attract large investment inflows. However, the Chinese government's emphasis on guiding FDI into manufacturing has led to market saturation in some industries, while leaving China's services sectors underdeveloped. From 1993 to 2001, China was the world's second-largest recipient of foreign direct investment after the United States. China received $39&nbsp;billion&nbsp;FDI in 1999 and $41&nbsp;billion&nbsp;FDI in 2000. China is now one of the leading FDI recipients in the world, receiving almost $80&nbsp;billion in 2005 according to World Bank statistics. In 2006, China received $69.47&nbsp;billion in foreign direct investment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/01/15/business/yuan.php |title=Foreign investment in China rebounds&nbsp;\u2013 |work=International Herald Tribune |date=15 January 2007 |access-date=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013101238/http://iht.com/articles/2007/01/15/business/yuan.php |archive-date=13 October 2007 |url-status=live }}</ref> By 2011, with the U.S. seeing a decline in foreign investment following the [[Financial crisis of 2007\u201308|2008 financial crisis]], China overtook it as the top destination for FDI, receiving over $280 billion that year.<ref>{{cite web|title = Foreign direct investment, net inflows (BoP, current US$) {{!}} Data {{!}} Table|url = http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/BX.KLT.DINV.CD.WD?order=wbapi_data_value_2014+wbapi_data_value+wbapi_data_value-last&sort=desc|publisher = World Bank|access-date = 29 January 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160217035319/http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/BX.KLT.DINV.CD.WD?order=wbapi_data_value_2014+wbapi_data_value+wbapi_data_value-last&sort=desc|archive-date = 17 February 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAmid slowing economic conditions and a weakening yuan in 2015, December of that year saw a 5.8% drop in FDI to China.<ref>{{cite news |author = Enda Curran |author2 = Jonathan Browning |title = Foreign Investment into China Falls as Weaker Yuan Dents Inflows |url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-20/foreign-investment-into-china-falls-as-weaker-yuan-dents-inflows |agency = Bloomberg |access-date = 29 January 2016 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160202103521/http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-01-20/foreign-investment-into-china-falls-as-weaker-yuan-dents-inflows |archive-date = 2 February 2016 |url-status = live }}</ref> While China's rank as the top receiver of FDI continued through 2014, the slowing of inbound investment in 2015 combined with a massive rebound in foreign investment to the United States resulted in the U.S. reclaiming its position as the top investment destination.<ref>{{cite news|title = U.S. Overtakes China as Top Destination for Foreign Investment|url = https://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-overtakes-china-as-top-destination-for-foreign-investment-1453312933|newspaper = The Wall Street Journal|first = Paul|last = Hannon|accessdate = 29 January 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160126110952/http://www.wsj.com/articles/u-s-overtakes-china-as-top-destination-for-foreign-investment-1453312933|archive-date = 26 January 2016|url-status = live}}</ref> Data from the American Chamber of Commerce in China's ''[http://www.amchamchina.org/policy-advocacy/business-climate-survey/ 2016 China Business Climate Survey]'' confirms this trend, although it also demonstrates that China remains a top investment destination. This survey of over 500 members found that \"China remains a top three investment priority for six out of ten member companies,\" though this is a decline from the 2012 high of eight out of ten respondents considering China a top priority.<ref>{{Cite book|title = 2016 China Business Climate Survey|publisher = American Chamber of Commerce in China|year = 2016|location = Beijing, China|pages = 4|url = http://www.amchamchina.org/policy-advocacy/business-climate-survey/|access-date = 29 January 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160210134259/http://www.amchamchina.org/policy-advocacy/business-climate-survey/|archive-date = 10 February 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n[[Foreign exchange reserve of the People's Republic of China|Foreign exchange reserves]] totaled $155&nbsp;billion in 1999 and $165&nbsp;billion in 2000. [[Foreign exchange reserves]] exceeded $800&nbsp;billion in 2005, more than doubling from 2003. Foreign exchange reserves were $819&nbsp;billion at the end of 2005, $1.066&nbsp;trillion at the end of 2006, $1.9&nbsp;trillion by June 2008. In addition, by the end of September 2008 China replaced Japan for the first time as the largest foreign holder of US treasury securities with a total of $585&nbsp;billion, vs Japan $573&nbsp;billion. China's foreign exchange reserves are the [[List of countries by foreign exchange reserves|largest in the world]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2188rank.html|title=The World Factbook \u2013 Central Intelligence Agency|website=www.cia.gov|access-date=28 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070613005020/https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/rankorder/2188rank.html|archive-date=13 June 2007|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAs part of its WTO accession, China undertook to eliminate certain trade-related investment measures and to open up specified sectors that had previously been closed to foreign investment. New laws, regulations, and administrative measures to implement these commitments are being issued. Major remaining barriers to foreign investment include opaque and inconsistently enforced laws and regulations and the lack of a rules-based legal infrastructure. Warner Bros., for instance, withdrew its cinema business in China as a result of a regulation that requires Chinese investors to own at least a 51 percent stake or play a leading role in a foreign joint venture.<ref>[http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-11/09/content_5310610.htm Warner Bros to withdraw from Chinese mainland] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013180017/http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2006-11/09/content_5310610.htm |date=13 October 2007 }} (Xinhuanet.com, with source from China Radio International)</ref>\n\nAnother major development in the history of foreign investment in China was the establishment of the [[Shanghai Free Trade Zone]] in September 2013.<ref>[http://www.china-briefing.com/news/2013/09/28/china-releases-general-plan-and-regulations-for-the-shanghai-free-trade-zone.html \"Shanghai's New Free Trade Zone \u2013 General Plan and Regulations\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225085323/http://www.china-briefing.com/news/2013/09/28/china-releases-general-plan-and-regulations-for-the-shanghai-free-trade-zone.html |date=25 February 2014 }}, ''China Briefing'', Shanghai, 28 September 2013</ref> The Zone is considered a testing ground for a number of economic and social reforms.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dw.de/china-opens-free-trade-zone-in-shanghai/a-17121642|title=China opens free trade zone in Shanghai|publisher=Deutsche Welle|access-date=8 May 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140708162731/http://www.dw.de/china-opens-free-trade-zone-in-shanghai/a-17121642|archive-date=8 July 2014|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.waigaoqiao.gov.cn/ |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010302131009/http://www.waigaoqiao.gov.cn/ |url-status=dead |archive-date=2 March 2001 |script-title=zh:\u4e2d\u56fd\uff08\u4e0a\u6d77\uff09\u81ea\u7531\u8d38\u6613\u8bd5\u9a8c\u533a\u95e8\u6237\u7f51\u7ad9 |language=zh-cn |publisher=waigaoqiao.gov.cn}}</ref> Critically, foreign investment is controlled via a \"negative list\" approach, where FDI is permitted in all sectors unless explicitly prohibited by the inclusion of a given sector on the [[negative list]] published by the [[Shanghai Municipal Government]].<ref>[http://www.china-briefing.com/news/2013/09/30/shanghai-releases-negative-list-for-foreign-investment-in-shanghai-free-trade-zone.html \"Shanghai Releases 'Negative List' for Foreign Investment in Shanghai Free Trade Zone\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718070100/http://www.china-briefing.com/news/2013/09/30/shanghai-releases-negative-list-for-foreign-investment-in-shanghai-free-trade-zone.html |date=18 July 2014 }}, ''China Briefing'', Shanghai, 9 September 2013.</ref>\n\nOn 15 March 2019, China's [[National People's Congress]] adopted the [[Foreign Investment Law of the People's Republic of China|Foreign Investment Law]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://mg2.mofcom.gov.cn/article/policy/China/201909/20190902898870.shtml|title=Foreign Investment Law of the People's Republic of China|website=mofcom.gov.cn|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191016070903/http://mg2.mofcom.gov.cn/article/policy/China/201909/20190902898870.shtml|archive-date=16 October 2019|access-date=2019-11-25}}</ref> which comes into effect on 1 January 2020.\n\n===Chinese investment abroad===\n[[File:TCL 4K tv (23851323683).jpg|thumb|A [[TCL Corporation|TCL]] television set]]\n[[File:Belt and Road Initiative participant map.svg|thumb|Countries which signed cooperation documents related to the [[Belt and Road Initiative]]]]\n\nOutward foreign direct investment is a new feature of Chinese globalization, where local Chinese firms seek to make investments in both developing and developed countries.<ref>Alon, Ilan and John McIntyre, eds. (2008), The Globalization of Chinese Enterprises, New York: Palgrave Macmillan.</ref> It was reported in 2011 that there was increasing investment by capital rich Chinese firms in promising firms in the United States. Such investments offer access to expertise in marketing and distribution potentially useful in exploiting the developing Chinese domestic market.<ref>{{cite news |title=A Wave of Chinese Money Gives a Lift to Companies Struggling in Tough Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/07/business/smallbusiness/07sbiz.html |newspaper=The New York Times |date=6 July 2011 |author=James Flanigan |access-date=7 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110709115550/http://www.nytimes.com/2011/07/07/business/smallbusiness/07sbiz.html |archive-date=9 July 2011 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSince 2005, Chinese companies have been actively expanding outside of China, in both developed and developing countries. In 2013, Chinese companies invested US$90 billion globally in non-financial sectors, 16% more than 2012.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ministry of Commerce of China |url=http://www.fdi.gov.cn/1800000121_33_3962_0_7.html |access-date=3 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714151358/http://www.fdi.gov.cn/1800000121_33_3962_0_7.html |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nBetween January 2009 and December 2013, China contributed a total of $161.03bn in outward [[Foreign direct investment|FDI]], creating almost 300,000 jobs. Western Europe was the largest regional recipient of Chinese outward FDI, with Germany receiving the highest number of FDI projects for any country globally.<ref>{{cite news|title=Where is China investing?|url=http://www.fdiintelligence.com/Locations/Asia-Pacific/China/Where-is-China-investing|newspaper=[[FDi Magazine]]|date=12 August 2014|access-date=21 August 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140821152738/http://www.fdiintelligence.com/Locations/Asia-Pacific/China/Where-is-China-investing|archive-date=21 August 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere are two ways Chinese companies choose to enter a foreign market: organic growth and Merge & Acquisition (M&A). Many Chinese companies would prefer M&A for the following reasons:\n* Fast. M&A is the fastest way for a company to expand into another country by acquiring brand, distribution, talents, and technology. Chinese CEOs has been used to growing at 50%+ speed and do not want to spend capital.\n* China market. China has become the world's largest economy. Many Chinese acquire foreign companies and then bring their products/services to China, anything from premium cars to fashion clothing to meat to Hollywood movies.\n* Cheap capital access. The huge Chinese domestic market help many Chinese companies accumulated financial capital to do M&A. Chinese government also provides long-term, low-interest capital for companies to expand abroad.\n* Low risk. M&A helped Chinese companies avoid risk of failure of organic growth as they got an established company with everything in place.\n* Cheap labor. Some companies may move part of the manufacturing in high labor cost countries to China to reduce the cost and make the product more attractive in price.\n* Trade and policy barrier. Chinese companies in many sectors face quota limitation and high tax, which prevent them from being competitive in foreign markets.\n* Depressed assets. 2008\u20132010 global economic crisis created liquidity problems for a lot of western companies and reduced their market value. Chinese companies believe it is a great opportunity for them to buy these depressed assets at discount. China's direct foreign investment in non-financial sector growth from US$25 billion in 2007 to US$90 billion in 2013, more than three times.<ref>{{cite news |date=30 October 2008 |script-title=zh:2007\u5e74\u5ea6\u4e2d\u56fd\u5168\u884c\u4e1a\u5bf9\u5916\u76f4\u63a5\u6295\u8d44\u7edf\u8ba1\u6570\u636e |language=zh-cn |trans-title=China's total foreign direct investment statistics for the whole year 2007 |publisher=China Daily |url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/hqzg/2008-10/30/content_7159288.htm |access-date=3 July 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714153206/http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/hqzg/2008-10/30/content_7159288.htm |archive-date=14 July 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*China is growing in investments and influencing power over Europe, and the EU has begun to take notice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/briefing/2018/10/04/chinese-investment-and-influence-in-europe-is-growing|title=Chinese investment, and influence, in Europe is growing|work=The Economist|access-date=8 October 2018|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181008183836/https://www.economist.com/briefing/2018/10/04/chinese-investment-and-influence-in-europe-is-growing|archive-date=8 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAt the beginning, state-owned enterprises dominate the foreign acquisition and most of the money goes to oil and minerals. Since 2005, more and more private companies start to acquire non-raw material foreign companies. Below is a list of the top 15 outbound deals from Chinese companies:<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://imaa-institute.org/m-and-a-in-china/|title=M&A in China \u2013 IMAA-Institute|work=IMAA-Institute|access-date=22 February 2018|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180222225839/https://imaa-institute.org/m-and-a-in-china/|archive-date=22 February 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Date\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Acquirer\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Acquirer industry\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Target\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Target industry\n!class=\"unsortable\"|Target country\n!Deal value in USD \n|-\n|3 February 2016\n|CNAC Saturn (NL) BV\n|Chemicals\n|[[Syngenta AG]]\n|Chemicals\n|Switzerland\n|41,840.11\n|-\n|23 July 2012\n|CNOOC Canada Holding Ltd\n|Other financials\n|[[Nexen Inc]]\n|Oil and gas\n|Canada\n|19,119.31\n|-\n|1 February 2008\n|Shining Prospect Pte Ltd\n|Other financials\n|[[Rio Tinto Group|Rio Tinto PLC]]\n|Metals and mining\n|United Kingdom\n|14,284.17\n|-\n|2 June 2017\n|China Investment Corp\n|Alternative financial investments\n|Logicor Ltd\n|Non residential\n|United Kingdom\n|13,742.43\n|-\n|14 July 2017\n|Nesta Investment Holdings Ltd\n|Other financials\n|Global Logistic Properties Ltd\n|Non residential\n|Singapore\n|11,553.58\n|-\n|22 August 2017\n|China Unicom (BVI) Ltd\n|Telecommunications services\n|China Unicom Hong Kong Ltd\n|Telecommunications services\n|Hong Kong\n|11,255.81\n|-\n|6 October 2016\n|Park Aerospace Holdings Ltd\n|Transportation and infrastructure\n|C2 Aviation Capital LLC\n|Transportation and infrastructure\n|United States\n|10,380.00\n|-\n|14 October 2015\n|China Tower Corp Ltd\n|Telecommunications services\n|China-Telecommun tower asts\n|Wireless\n|China\n|9,948.41\n|-\n|21 June 2016\n|Halti SA\n|Other financials\n|[[Supercell Oy]]\n|Software\n|Finland\n|8,600.00\n|-\n|24 June 2009\n|Mirror Lake Oil & Gas Co Ltd\n|Oil and gas\n|[[Addax Petroleum]] Corp\n|Oil and gas\n|Switzerland\n|7,157.40\n|-\n|1 October 2010\n|China Petrochemical Corp\n|Oil and gas\n|Repsol YPF Brasil SA\n|Oil and gas\n|Brazil\n|7,111.00\n|-\n|16 March 2016\n|Anbang Insurance Group Co Ltd\n|Insurance\n|Strategic Hotels & Resorts Inc\n|REITs\n|United States\n|6,500.00\n|-\n|24 October 2016\n|Hna Tourism Grp Co Ltd\n|Travel services\n|[[Hilton Worldwide Holdings Inc]]\n|Hotels and lodging\n|United States\n|6,496.88\n|-\n|17 February 2016\n|Tianjin Tianhai Invest Co Ltd\n|Transportation and infrastructure\n|Ingram Micro Inc\n|Computers and peripherals\n|United States\n|6,067.41\n|-\n|22 March 2015\n|Marco Polo Industrial Hldg SpA\n|Other financials\n|[[Pirelli]] & C SpA\n|Automobiles and components\n|Italy\n|\n|}\n\nHowever, the fast growth and M&A deals did not change consumers' low quality and low price perception of Chinese goods and brands. According to market consecutive researches by the Monogram Group, a Chicago-based advertising agency, in 2007, 2009, 2011 and 2012, American consumers' willingness to purchase Chinese products across all categories except PC remained the same or became worse during 2007\u20132012. The only sector in which Americans were more likely to purchase was personal computers.<ref>American Consumer's Attitude towards China and Chinese Brands (2007, 2009, 2011, 2012), The Monogram Group.</ref>\n[[File:Inauguracja po\u0142\u0105czenia kolejowego \u201eChina Railway Express\u201d.jpg|thumb|China's President [[Xi Jinping]] and [[Poland]]'s President [[Andrzej Duda]] during the inauguration of the [[Yiwu\u2013London railway line|China Railway Express]] in Warsaw, Poland, 20 June 2016]]\nMoreover, many M&A deals have failed because companies underestimated the challenges and failed to restructure the company.\n\nCase 1: Shanghai Auto acquired 48.9% of Korean Ssangyong at US$500 million in 2004, making it the most ambitious acquisition in Chinese auto industry at the time. Shanghai Auto wanted the brand and technology to expand its footprint in China. However, the cultural difference, the objection to transfer the technology and the failed sales of new SUV model put Shanghai Auto's ambition of expansion in jeopardy. It caused huge conflict between Ssangyong employees and Shanghai Auto as things didn't go well as planned. And the 2008 global economic crisis put Ssangyong on a survival mode, let alone expansion. After the negotiation with the labor union to reduce wages failed, Shanghai Auto decided to exit from Ssangyong and didn't get a penny back for their US$500 million investment.<ref>{{cite news |first = Andrew |last = Salmon |date=29 October 2004 |title = Shanghai Automotive expands with Korea purchase |newspaper = The New York Times |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2004/10/29/business/worldbusiness/29iht-ssang_ed3_.html }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last = Choe |first = Sang-Hun |date = 24 February 2009 |title = In Carmaker's Collapse, a Microcosm of South Korea's Woes |newspaper = The New York Times |url = https://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/24/world/asia/24seoul.html?pagewanted=all |page = A6 |access-date = 18 February 2017 |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160723022736/http://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/24/world/asia/24seoul.html?pagewanted=all |archive-date = 23 July 2016 |url-status = live }}</ref>\n\nCase 2: In 2004, the television manufacturer TCL acquired TV business including Thomson and RCA brand from Thomson Electronics of France to form a joint vendure called TCL-Thomson Electronics (TTE). For the coming two years, the company recorded huge loss, especially in Europe. Several factors contributed to the failure:\n* Failure of Due Diligence. Right after TCL acquired Thomson's TV business, the TV market shifted to LCD technology, put Thomson out of date. As CEO of TCL, Dongsheng Li, said in 2012 \"They betted on the wrong thing where the market would go. They thought Thomson's DLP could be the best choice.\"\n* Lack of understanding of rules and regulations. According to the book ''Resumption of Trading'' by Chong Chen, soon after acquisition, Thomson found it in a situation that they couldn't recruit the talents they wanted and can't fire ones they didn't want.\n* Underestimate of the challenges in cultural difference. Xuesong Tong, vice president of TTE, said in an interview with \"China Operation\" newspaper in 2005: \"The French look down upon their Chinese boss. For example, they wanted to share the design model with TTE, but French just dislike it even though it is a popular one in US market. Also, French feel superior in their language and don't want to speak English, which created huge problem in communication. It takes hours to discuss simple issues and can't reach agreement.\"\n* According to Scott Markman, president of Monogram, Chinese companies often moved their business model to developed countries and it doesn't work. Thomson has the problem, they are very good and distribution and operation in China but France and Europe is a totally different world.{{Citation needed|date=August 2016}}\n\n===Mergers and acquisitions===\nFrom 1993 to 2010, Chinese companies have been involved as either an acquiror or acquired company in 25,284 [[mergers and acquisitions]] with a total known value of US$969 billion.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imaa-institute.org/statistics-mergers-acquisitions.html#MergersAcquisitions_China |title=Statistics on Mergers & Acquisitions (M&A) \u2013 M&A Courses &#124; Company Valuation Courses &#124; Mergers & Acquisitions Courses |publisher=Imaa-institute.org |accessdate=27 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120106045040/http://www.imaa-institute.org/statistics-mergers-acquisitions.html#MergersAcquisitions_China |archive-date=6 January 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref> The number and value of deals hit a new record in 2010. The number of deals that happened in 2010 has been 3,640, which is an increase of 17% compared to 2009. The value of deals in 2010 was US$196 billion, which is an increase of 25% compared to the year before.\n\n== Demographics ==\n{{Main|Demographics of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Further|Migration in the People's Republic of China|Urbanization in the People's Republic of China|Chinese emigration|Standard of living in the People's Republic of China|Poverty in the People's Republic of China}}\n\nSince the 1950s [[medical care]], [[public hygiene]] and [[Sanitation in China|sanitation]] improved considerably, and [[epidemics]] were controlled. Consecutive generations continuously experienced better health. The [[population growth]] rate surged as the [[mortality rate]] dropped more rapidly than the [[birth rate]]. China's massive population has always been a major difficulty for the government as it has struggled to provide for it. In the 1950s, food supply was inadequate and the standard of living was generally low. This spurred the authorities to initiate a major [[birth control]] program. The Great Leap Forward industrial plan in 1958\u201360 was partially responsible for a huge [[Great Chinese Famine|famine]] that caused the death rate to surpass the birth rate, and by 1960, the overall population was declining. A second [[population control]] drive began in 1962 with major efforts focused on promoting late marriages and the use of [[contraceptive]]s. By 1963 the country was in the beginning of recovery from the famine and the birth rate soared to its highest since 1949 with an annual population growth rate of 3%. In 1966, the Cultural Revolution suspended this second [[family planning]] program, but resumed four years later with the third attempt by making later marriage and family size limitation an obligation. Since 1970, the efforts have been much more effective. The third family planning program continued until 1979 when the [[one-child policy|one child per family policy]] was implemented. By the early 1980s, China's population reached around 1&nbsp;billion and by the early 2000s, surpassed 1.3&nbsp;billion. In the 1980s, the average overall population growth was around 1.5%. In the 1990s, this fell to about 1%. Today it is about 0.6%.<ref>[[List of countries by population growth rate]]</ref> China's [[population growth rate]] is now among the lowest for a [[developing country]], although, due to its large population, annual net population growth is still considerable. One demographic consequence of the one-child policy is that China is now one of the most rapidly [[Population ageing|ageing]] countries in the world.\n\nFrom 100&nbsp;million to 150&nbsp;million surplus rural workers are adrift between the villages and the cities, many subsisting through part-time, low-paying jobs.\n\nAccording to the latest [[Forbes China Rich List]] (2007), China had 66 [[billionaire]]s, the second largest number after the [[Forbes 400|United States]], which had 415. In the 2006 Forbes Rich List it stated that there were 15 Chinese billionaires.<ref>[http://www.iht.com/articles/2007/11/06/business/billionaires.php?page=1 The newest billionaires: China's economy churns out dozens]. International Herald Tribune. 6 November 2007.</ref> In the latest 2007 Hurun Report, it lists 106 billionaires in China.<ref>[http://www.hurun.net/richlisten.aspx 2007 China Rich List series] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101228072246/http://www.hurun.net/richlisten.aspx |date=28 December 2010 }}. Hurun Report.</ref>\n\n===Labor force===\nIn 2012, for the first time, according to statistics released by China's National Bureau of Statistics in January 2013, the size of the labor force, people aged 15 to 59, in China shrank slightly to 937.27 million people, a decrease of 3.45 million from 2011. This trend, resulting from China's one-child policy of population control, is anticipated to continue to at least 2030.\n\nOn 29 October 2015, Xinhua, China's state news agency, reported a change in the existing law to a two-child policy, citing a statement from the Communist Party of China, and the new law is effective from 1 January 2016 after it was passed in the standing committee of the National People's Congress on 27 December 2015.<ref name=\"CNBC011913\">{{cite news |title=Chinese Labor Pool Begins to Drain |url=https://www.cnbc.com/id/100392731 |publisher=CNBC |date=19 January 2013 |author=Jamil Anderliniin |author2=Ed Crooks |agency=Financial Times |accessdate=8 February 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130328064737/http://www.cnbc.com/id/100392731 |archive-date=28 March 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Transportation and infrastructure==\n{{main|Transport in China}}\n\n[[File:A maglev train coming out, Pudong International Airport, Shanghai.jpg|thumb|[[Shanghai Maglev Train]]]]\nChina's transportation policy, influenced by political, military, and economic concerns, have undergone major changes since 1949.<ref>[[Fengbo Zhang]]: [http://sites.google.com/site/chinesetransportation1/ Economic Analysis of Chinese Transportation] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110926172608/http://sites.google.com/site/chinesetransportation1/ |date=26 September 2011 }}</ref>\n\nImmediately after the People's Republic was founded, the primary goal was to repair existing transportation infrastructure in order to meet [[military transport]] and [[Military logistics|logistics]] needs as well as to strengthen territorial integrity. During most of the 1950s, new road and rail links were built, while at the same time old ones were improved. During the 1960s much of the improvement of regional transportation became the responsibility of the local governments, and many small railways were constructed. Emphasis was also placed on developing transportation in remote rural, mountainous, and forested areas, in order to integrate poorer regions of the country and to help promote economies of scale in the agricultural sector.\n\nBefore the reform era began in the late 1970s, China's transportation links were mostly concentrated in the coastal areas and access to the inner regions was generally poor. This situation has been improved considerably since then, as railways and highways have been built in the remote and frontier regions of the northwest and southwest. At the same time, the development of international transportation was also pursued, and the scope of [[ocean shipping]] was broadened considerably.\n\n[[Freight]] [[Logistics|haulage]] is mainly provided by [[rail transport]]. The rail sector is monopolized by [[China Railway]] and there is wide variation in services provided. In late 2007 China became one of the few countries in the world to launch its own indigenously developed [[High-speed rail|high-speed train]].<ref>{{cite news |url = http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jZHR0k1z-KAzmdB46eKOuFFqHuSQ |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071226161506/http://afp.google.com/article/ALeqM5jZHR0k1z-KAzmdB46eKOuFFqHuSQ |url-status=dead |archive-date=26 December 2007 |title=China produces first home-grown bullet train: report |date=22 December 2007 |accessdate=28 February 2012 }}</ref> As rail capacity is struggling to meet demand for the transport of goods and raw materials such as coal, air routes, roads and waterways are rapidly being developed to provide an increasing proportion of China's overall transportation needs.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8760cdcc-a41e-11dc-a28d-0000779fd2ac,dwp_uuid=f6e7043e-6d68-11da-a4df-0000779e2340.html |title=China: Logistics is key to inland shift |newspaper=Financial Times |date=10 December 2007 |accessdate=28 February 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080307092413/http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/8760cdcc-a41e-11dc-a28d-0000779fd2ac,dwp_uuid=f6e7043e-6d68-11da-a4df-0000779e2340.html |archive-date=7 March 2008 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nSome economic experts have argued that the development gap between China and other emerging economies such as Brazil, Argentina and India can be attributed to a large extent to China's early focus on ambitious infrastructure projects: while China invested roughly 9% of its GDP on infrastructure in the 1990s and 2000s, most emerging economies invested only 2% to 5% of their GDP. This considerable spending gap allowed the Chinese economy to grow at near optimal conditions while many South American economies suffered from various development bottlenecks such as poor transportation networks, aging power grids and mediocre schools.<ref>{{cite news |first1 = Vincent |last1 = Bazi |first2 = M. Nicolas J. |last2 = Firzli |year=2011 |title = Infrastructure Investments in an Age of Austerity : The Pension and Sovereign Funds Perspective |url = http://www.turkishweekly.net/op-ed/2852/infrastructure-investments-in-an-age-of-austerity-the-pension-and-sovereign-funds-perspective.html |newspaper=Revue Analyse Financi\u00e8re |volume=41 |issue=Q4|pages=19\u201322 |url-status=dead |archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110917182931/http://www.turkishweekly.net/op-ed/2852/infrastructure-investments-in-an-age-of-austerity-the-pension-and-sovereign-funds-perspective.html |archive-date=17 September 2011 |df = dmy }}</ref>\n\n== Science and technology ==\n{{Main|Science and technology in the People's Republic of China}}\n\n[[File:TencentLogo.png|thumb|200px|upright|[[Tencent]], one of the world's most valuable technology conglomerates]]\n\n[[Science and technology in China]] has in recent decades developed rapidly. The Chinese government has placed emphasis through funding, reform, and societal status on science and technology as a fundamental part of the socio-economic development of the country as well as for national prestige. China has made rapid advances in areas such as education, infrastructure, high-tech manufacturing, artificial intelligence,<ref>{{cite web |last1=Allen |first1=Gregory |title=Understanding China's AI Strategy |url=https://www.cnas.org/publications/reports/understanding-chinas-ai-strategy |website=Understanding China's AI Strategy |publisher=Center for a New American Security |accessdate=11 March 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190317004017/https://www.cnas.org/publications/reports/understanding-chinas-ai-strategy |archive-date=17 March 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> [[academic publishing]], [[patent]]s and commercial applications and is now in some areas and by some measures a world leader. China is now increasingly targeting indigenous [[innovation]] and aims to reform remaining weaknesses. These initiatives are dependent on attracting highly educated overseas Chinese back to China to work in the innovation economy and to teach the next generation of Chinese students.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|China|Economics|Business and economics}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=22em|\n* [[Center for China in the World Economy]], [[Tsinghua University]], Beijing\n* [[Central Financial Work Commission]]\n* [[China Beijing Equity Exchange]]\n* [[China Circle]]\n* [[China Economic Databases]] (CED) (China Studies Center, [[National Chengchi University]], Taiwan)\n* [[China Milan Equity Exchange]]\n* [[Economy of the Han Dynasty]]\n* [[Economy of the Ming Dynasty]]\n* [[Economy of the Song Dynasty]]\n* [[Elizabeth Economy]] (China economy and environment expert)\n* [[Energy policy of China]]\n* [[Foreign Investment Law of the People's Republic of China]]\n* [[Grasping the large, letting go of the small]] (policy)\n* [[Guo jin min tui]]\n* [[Historical GDP of the People's Republic of China|Historical GDP]]\n* [[Hukou system]]\n* [[Imperial Bank of China]]\n* [[Leading stock]]s\n* [[List of companies of the People's Republic of China]]\n* [[List of the largest companies of China]]\n* [[Oil shale in China]]\n* [[Panda bonds]]\n* [[Rural credit cooperative]]\n* [[Silk Road]]\n* ''[[The Chinese Economy: Transitions and Growth]]'' (book)\n* [[Township and Village Enterprises]] (TVEs)\n* [[Three Rural Issues]]\n* [[Tuangou]]\n* [[Yangtze River Delta]]\n}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== 